<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Official Explains Market Access Offers to WTO </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official today
explained China's market access offers to WTO members at the fifth
meeting of the Working Party on China's Accession to the World
Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
Long Yongtu, China's chief trade representative and vice
foreign trade minister, said the Chinese side has once again
revised several annexes to the Accession Protocol and further
enhanced the transparency of its foreign trade regime after a
series of difficult coordination at home.
</P>
<P>
"The firm political commitment of the Chinese government to a
early accession to the WTO has been translated into concrete
actions" in the current round of negotiations, he said.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that China's market access offers have been
substantially improved in the following areas:
</P>
<P>
- The Chinese government has decided to give up the right to
reintroduce export subsidies for agricultural products. This is a
new and major contribution the Chinese government has made to
strengthening the world multilateral trading system.
</P>
<P>
- The Chinese government has decided to make drastic and
cross-the-board reduction of the phase-out schedule of non-tariff
measures (NTMs).
</P>
<P>
China is prepared to shorten the phase-out period for 86 items
from the original 12 years to eight years which include
automobiles and auto parts, and has proposed maximum reduction of
the phase-out schedule of the remaining NTMs.
</P>
<P>
To ensure a smooth elimination of the NTMs, China has also
proposed annual growth rates of the quota volume, ranging from 8
percent to 12 percent, during the transition, which will provide
foreign suppliers of automobile, other machinery and electronic
products of all WTO members with a gradually expanding market
access opportunity.
</P>
<P>
- Regarding tariffs, China has held tariff negotiations with
nearly 20 WTO members before this Working Party meeting. In the
course of such negotiations, the Chinese side has made progress
with all members to a different extent, and major progress with
some of them.
</P>
<P>
China has substantially improved its offers to all negotiating
partners, tabled the harmonized tariff proposal for over 2000
chemical and textile products, and further improved offers on auto
and auto parts, paper and paper products, some electrical home
appliances and agricultural products.
</P>
<P>
Once its tariff concession proposal comes into force, China's
overall average tariff level will be lower than the 15-percent
average tariff level already announced by the Chinese government.
</P>
</TEXT>
