<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Former British MPs Criticized by Parliament Committee </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Four former British Conservative
MPs were criticized today by the Commons Standards Committee of
the British parliament.
</P>
<P>
The committee said former minister Tim Smith was found to have
accepted at least 18,000 pounds (29,500 U.S. dollars) from Mohamed
Al-Fayed, owner of upmarket London store Harrods, but had failed
adequately to declare he was working for Al-Fayed in the register
of MPs' interests.
</P>
<P>
The money was judged to have been in return for lobbying
services, the committee said.
</P>
<P>
It also recorded a similar verdict against Sir Michael Grylls, who
retired after 27 years as an MP at the May 1 election, saying he
had "deliberately misled" a Committee on Members' Interests about
lobbying fees he had received.
</P>
<P>
Two other former MPs, Michael Brown and Sir Andrew Bowden, were
less severely censured. Bowden has apologized for failing to
register an election donation of 5,319 pounds from lobbyist Ian
Greer. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
