<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Business Liquidations Up in S. Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Business liquidations
increased 23 percent for the second quarter of this year as high
interest rates, a contraction of spending and the globalization
of the South African economy took their toll.
</P>
<P>
However, figures released by the Central Statistical Service
(CSS) showed that the sharp rise in liquidations was offset by a
9 percent drop in insolvencies for three months until May,
the local daily Business Day reported today.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the CSS figures indicated that about 850
corporations and companies had been placed under final
liquidation compared with 690 for the second quarter last year.
</P>
<P>
There were 607 insolvencies during the period of March to May,
compared with 666 for the same period last year, said the CSS. It
added that the figure for insolvencies refers only to the number
of individuals and partnerships under final sequestration, not
the total number of people involved.
</P>
<P>
The general trend was a sideways movement, despite short-term
fluctuations, and the rising numbers of compulsory liquidations
of companies were still behind the upward trend, CSS said.
</P>
<P>
The number of voluntary liquidations fell 10 percent, owing to
a 20.9 percent drop in voluntary liquidations of closed
corporations.
</P>
<P>
Compulsory liquidations, however, increased 8.9 percent as
against the first quarter, it added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
