<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Floods Hit Grains Production in Central Europe </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The severe flooding in central
Europe will significantly reduce grains production in the
countries of that area, according to the British newspaper The
Financial Times today.
</P>
<P>
Countries such as Poland, the Czech and Slovak republics and
Romania have suffered worst flooding for many years, which has
caused enormous damage to farming of those countries.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted a grains specialist as saying, "It's too early
to say exactly how much the harvests will be affected in terms of
quantity, but it's absolutely clear that their quality will be
seriously damaged."
</P>
<P>
The International Grains Council (IGC) published its latest
world grains estimates for the current season, and revised
downwards its forecasts for central Europe.
</P>
<P>
The IGC now projects wheat production for the region will be
down by 1.5 million tons, to 32.4 million tons; at the start of
July its estimate was 33.9 million tons.
</P>
<P>
However, the reduced figure will still be considerably higher
than the 26.3 million tons harvested in 1996, according to some
grains specialists.
</P>
<P>
Poland, which along with eastern Germany has been the most
badly affected part of the region, is now forecast to see its
wheat crop reduced by 300,000 tons, to 7.9 million tons compared
with 8.5 million tons in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Poland imported 1.8 million tons of wheat last year, and the
IGC was anticipating before the floods that it would import no
more than 500,000 tons this year.
</P>
<P>
But with some 140,000 hectares of grain fields swamped in its
southern and south-western areas, most analysts believe that
Poland's wheat imports will eventually match if not outstrip last
year's.
</P>
<P>
One specialist said he now anticipated overall losses of as
much as 2 million tons from the region, but added that this
figure was being constantly revised in light of the continuing
floods. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
