<HEADLINE> Yeltsin Condemns Terrorist Act in Jerusalem </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin
today condemned the terrorist acts in Jerusalem which took place
Wednesday and claimed 15 lives of innocent people, the Itar-Tass
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin called the latest terrorist acts in Jerusalem a tragedy
and expressed condolences to families of the deceased and wounded.
</P>
<P>
He said that he sent a special letter to the Israeli
leadership, asking them to bring his condolences to each family.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Yeltsin noted that he favors Palestine Liberation
Organization leader Yasser Arafat's decision to arrest the leaders
of the main terrorist groups, one of which, in Yeltsin's opinion,
is responsible for the committed "unheard-of terrorist act."
</P>
<P>
Yeltsin said that his recent talks with Israeli Prime Minister
Binyamin Netanyahu and Arafat have confirmed that the two sides
are divided by sharp difference.
</P>
<P>
The construction of a Jewish settlement is inconsistent with
the Land for Peace principle guiding the Middle East peace
process, he added.
</P>
<P>
The president told reporters that Israelis have not started
settling on lands in Arab areas of Jerusalem, although the two
sides proclaimed the slogan "Peace in exchange of Land."
</P>
<P>
"Therefore," he said, "if they left lands, it could be possible
to sign a peace treaty." 
</P>
</TEXT>
