<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tanzania's Tourism Earns More in 1996 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The government of Tanzania
earned 322 million U.S. Dollars from 326,194 tourists who visited
the country in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Presenting budget estimates for her Ministry for 1997/98
fiscal year at the National Assembly in Dodoma, central Tanzania
today, Natural Resources and Tourism Minister Zakia Meghji, said
that this was 24.3 percent increase over 1995.
</P>
<P>
She said, however, that the tourism growth trend was small in
comparison with the vast variety of tourism attractions available
in the country.
</P>
<P>
The minister attributed the small tourism market to poor
infrastructure, particularly roads which leads to the northern
tourist destinations.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, she said, Tanzania is not easily accessible by
tourists markets abroad due to very few international airlines
flying to Tanzania, compared to the neighboring countries.
</P>
<P>
Meghji said the government has prepared an intergrated tourism
master plan aimed at promoting the sector. She said the first
phase of the program to start this year would involve development
of the tourist circuits.
</P>
<P>
Feasibility studies for developing the coastal belt as well as
historical buildings for tourism would also be undertaken in this
phase, the minister said, adding that the European Union has
pledged to provide fund for this phase. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
