<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Free Food Distribution System in Rwanda </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The U. N. World Food Program
(WFP) today announced that a major operation of free food rations
distribution in the refugee-ridden Rwanda has been completed,
catering for large numbers of refugees.
</P>
<P>
In a news release issued here, WFP said that since the end of
January 1997, about 1.2 million Rwandan refugees have been
receiving a food basket monthly for food resettlement rations.
</P>
<P>
The rehabilitation of the agricultural production systems
would be the main tasks this year, according to WFP.
</P>
<P>
In November 1996, more than one million Rwandan refugees
started returning home from camps in former Zaire and Tanzania,
said the news release, adding that in view of the developments,
WFP worked out a six-month free food rations program.
</P>
<P>
The program was designed to help refugees quickly return to
their home villages, and rebuild their homes and rehabilitate
their farms, the release noted.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that WFP planned to focus its operations in
Rwanda for the remaining time of 1997 on the rehabilitation of
the agricultural production systems and destroyed infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
Areas which are prone to drought and crop failure will
continue to receive a large share of food assistance, it added.
</P>
<P>
According to recent WFP Crop and Food Supply estimates, the
total crop production in Rwanda will increase only marginally
while it will have to feed 1.6 million more people this year than
last year due to the influx of returning refugees.
</P>
<P>
The WFP report predicted that the output of pulses, which is
the main source of protein for most Rwandans, for this season is
expected to fall by 25 percent compared with last season.
</P>
<P>
The release said that some 450,000 Rwandans would continue to
be assisted through WFP food-for-work projects. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
