<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Greek Cypriot side is ready
to go to Switzerland for the second round of U.N.-led direct
talks, government spokesman Manolis Christofides said here today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters, the spokesman expressed the hope that
the Turkish Cypriot side will also respond positively and there
will be good will and cooperation toward a settlement of the
Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
President Glafcos Clerides and Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf
Denktash held their first round of face-to-face talks under the
U.N. auspices near New York from July 9-12 and agreed to continue
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
Few days ago, however, Denktash warned that he would not attend
the second round of direct talks, scheduled for August 11 to 16 in
Switzerland, after the European Union reaffirmed last month a
decision to begin considering Cyprus' EU membership early next
year.
</P>
<P>
Local reports said Denktash will announce his final decision
next Monday.
</P>
<P>
The Cyprus problem has remained unresolved since 1974 when the
island was divided after Turkish troops invaded and took over the
northern third in the wake of a failed pro-Athens coup.
</P>
<P>
The spokesman said the National Council, the top advisory body
to the President on the Cyprus problem, will meet next Thursday to
discuss a U.N. document presented to the two sides by Special
Advisor of the U.N. Secretary-General on Cyprus, Diego Cordovez,
during the first round of talks.
</P>
<P>
He stressed that "irrespective of progress to be made in
Switzerland, the question of missing persons should be resolved."
</P>
<P>
A total of 1,619 Greek Cypriots and Greeks were unaccounted for
after Turkey landed more than 30,000 troops on the eastern
Mediterranean island.
</P>
<P>
Clerides and Denktash agreed Thursday to work together to end
the file of those listed as missing, Greek and Turkish Cypriots,
by exchanging information on the location of graves and, to the
best extent possible, have the remains of those dead returned to
their families. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
