<HEADLINE> Tunisian President Voices Concern over Stalemated </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TUNIS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Tunisian President Zine Al-Abidine
Ben Ali today voiced deep concern over the stalemated Middle East
peace process caused by the Israeli settlement policy inside and
outside Jerusalem, the Tunisia-Africa News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at the closing session of the symposium of the
Tunisian overseas ambassadors and head of diplomatic missions,
the president urged the international community to take speedy
and decisive actions in order to save the regional peace process
and ward off the dangers facing the region.
</P>
<P>
The actions should ensure the restoration of the legitimate
rights of the Palestinian people and the establishment of its
independent state with Jerusalem as its capital, he said.
</P>
<P>
These actions should also ensure the restoration of the
occupied Syrian and Lebanese territories, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the EU-Mideast dialogue, the Tunisian president said
that its actual take-off and success require settling the Middle
East dispute on the one hand and achieving the balance of
interests, solidarity and equal partnership on the other.
</P>
<P>
The dialogue should deal with all issues on the future of the
EU-Mideast region and not stop at the security dimension, so as
to consolidate the mutual trust, understanding and coordination
among all countries of the region, he underlined.
</P>
<P>
The annual symposium of the Tunisian heads of diplomatic and
consular missions opened last Wednesday here under the title "the
diplomatic action at the service of economic development."
</P>
