<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ousted S. Leonean President Condemns Junta's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Sierra Leone's ousted President
Ahmed Tejan Kabbah today condemned the decision of the military
junta to stay in power for four years and accused politicians of
manipulating the regime.
</P>
<P>
"This is an affront to all lovers of democracy and smacks of
hostility," Kabbah said on a clandestine, anti-junta radio station
broadcasting in the capital Freetown, quoted by a report reaching
here.
</P>
<P>
Military ruler Major Johnny Paul Koroma, who seized power in
the May 25 coup that toppled Kabbah's elected government,
announced on Wednesday that the junta "will not hand over power
to a civilian government" until presidential election is held in
November 2001.
</P>
<P>
His announcement immediately led to the collapse of the peace
talks in session in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire, between junta
delegates and the Committee of Four, made up of foreign ministers
of Nigeria, Ghana, Guinea and Cote d'Ivoire.
</P>
<P>
The committee represents the Economic Community of West
African States (ECOWAS) to bid for reinstating Kabbah.
</P>
<P>
Koroma's new position also incurred condemnation from the
Commonwealth which suspended Sierra Leone's membership last month
as well as "deep concern" of the United Nations Security Council.
</P>
<P>
"Those who are bent on destroying the country would themselves
be destroyed," warned Kabbah in the broadcast, who has been in
Guinea since the coup.
</P>
<P>
"They will be hunted down even if they hide in rat holes," he
said.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah said the junta had adopted a "defiant and
uncompromising stand" because of advice from certain politicians
who "are manipulating the soldiers and urging them to stay in
power. But they shall not succeed".
</P>
<P>
He accused the politicians of "inciting the military to seize
power and promising them that the international community would
recognize them".
</P>
<P>
The ECOWAS Committee of Four earlier asked the Koroma regime
to hand over power to Kabbah's government or it would employ
embargo or even force to oust the military junta.
</P>
<P>
However, analysts noted it could be difficult to reach a
consensus among west African countries on ways to deal with
Koroma. Ghana has announced its aversion to the use of force in
resolving the Sierra Leone crisis. Cote d'Ivoire is reported in
similar view.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Koroma has said the ruling Armed Forces
Revolutionary Council, the highest governing body set up after
the coup, is "ready to defend the sovereignty of Sierra Leone to
the last drop of its blood".
</P>
<P>
As a matter of fact, the blockade by the ECOWAS peace-keeping
force has resulted in short supply of foodstuffs and drugs in the
troubled west African country.
</P>
<P>
The Committee of Four has called for a tightening of economic
sanctions to force the step-down of the junta after the collapse
of the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
