<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poor Nigerians Turn to Worms for Cheap Protein </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Some residents in Abuja, capital
of Nigeria, have found a substitute for hard-to-come-by protein
in caterpillar worms as the hairy crawlers are now ready diet for
them, the News Agency of Nigeria reported today.
</P>
<P>
Scores of youths and the elderly can now be seen in open
fields collecting the worms, attracting the attention of curious
passers-by within the last few weeks.
</P>
<P>
The worms caught are either for sell at the market or for
consumption in homes of these cash-strapped residents.
</P>
<P>
According to the official news agency, the worms sell for
about 50 Naira (some 0.59 U.S. dollar) per kilogram, as against
180 Naira (about 2.11 dollars) per kilogram of meat in the
market.
</P>
<P>
It said residents in Abuja started eating the worms "in
retaliation" for the destructive activity of the insects, which
usually invade farmlands and eat up the green leaves, thereby
decimating yields.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted an old woman seen collecting the worms as
saying that the worms were "very good when cooked with
vegetables" and the people in the area had eaten worms for
decades without any serious side effect.
</P>
<P>
"The worms provide our home with 'meat' since we do not have
the money to buy real meat or fish," she said, adding that "my
soup now tastes better with the worms."
</P>
<P>
The old woman also made a little money from the sales of the
warms at the market, the report said.
</P>
<P>
According to the report, the worms are already finding favor
with the non-indigenous who have also ventured into having a
taste of the boneless worms if only to provide a cheap substitute
to meat that they could hardly afford now.
</P>
<P>
However, the booming worms business may soon crash as
excessive downpour drives the worms into hibernation, the report
said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
