<HEADLINE> Georgia Wants Russian Peacekeepers to Stay in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Georgian President Eduard
Shevardnadze today expressed the hope that the Russian
peacekeepers will continue to tackle the issue in the Abkhazian
conflict zone, the Itar-Tass news agency reported from Tbilisi,
Georgia.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference, Shevardnadze said that the
Georgian leadership has not felt any pressure of Russia in
consideration of the stay of Russian peacekeeping troops in the
Abkhazian conflict zone.
</P>
<P>
In the opinion of the president, the next Commonwealth of
Independent States (CIS) summit should consider the stay of
Russian peacekeepers in the zone. "The problem of a stay of
Russian peacekeeping troops, a possibility to extend their mandate
and expediency of the prolonged peacekeeping operation, shall be
discussed and solved at the next meeting of the CIS Council of
State Heads," he noted.
</P>
<P>
Shevardnadze said that Georgia keeps to a peaceful way in the
settlement of the Abkhazian conflict. "The absolute majority of
Georgian residents and its leaders are strongly against a military
solution to the Abkhazian conflict," he added.
</P>
<P>
The president said that he has not had telephone conversations
with vacationing Russian President Boris Yeltsin in the recent
past.
</P>
<P>
He noted, "If the peacekeeping operation held in Abkhazia under
the CIS aegis fails to bring positive results, restore Georgian
territorial unity and return refugees to Abkhazia, Georgia
reserves the right to appeal in future to other international
organizations and countries, including the United Nations and NATO,
with a request to take part in a multinational peacekeeping
operation in Abkhazia aimed to restore Georgian unity and return
of refugees to Abkhazia."
</P>
<P>
According to another report, Georgia's National Security
Council "thinks it possible not to speed up" the withdrawal of
peacekeeping forces from the zone of the Georgia-Abkhazian
conflict.
</P>
<P>
The council in its statement said the decision to this effect
was taken with account of the positions of the "U.N. Security
Council, Georgia's Friends group of states (the United States,
Russian, France, Great Britain, Germany) and U.N. Secretary
General Kofi Annan, warning of a possible aggravation of tension
if the CIS peacekeepers are withdrawn from the conflict zone at
the current stage." 
</P>
</TEXT>
