<BODY>
<HEADLINE> US Factory Orders Climb Up Again in Three Months </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- This country's factory orders
rose 1.2 percent in June, the second advance in three months, the
Commerce Department said here today.
</P>
<P>
Orders for both durable and nondurable goods totaled a
seasonally adjusted 327.9 billion U.S. dollars, up from 324
billion dollars in May.
</P>
<P>
The backlog of unfilled orders increased 0.3 percent, also the
second advance in three months. A growing backlog could mean
businesses may have to increase production facilities and manpower
to meet demand.
</P>
<P>
Orders for durable goods, items such as computers and
communications equipment jumped 2.4 percent in June, erasing a 0.4
percent drop a month earlier. It was the biggest advance since
they shot up 3.4 percent in January.
</P>
<P>
The monthly increase was led by a 7.9 percent gain in
transportation orders including both aircraft and motor vehicles.
But excluding this sector, orders inched up just 0.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
In other durable goods sectors, orders for electronic and other
electrical equipment edged up 0.2 percent and for primary metals,
0.3 percent. But demand for industrial machinery and equipment
fell 0.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
Orders for nondurable goods such as paper and petroleum
products dipped 0.3 percent, also the second consecutive drop.
</P>
<P>
Orders for nonmilitary capital goods, excluding aircraft, rose
1.7 percent after falling 0.6 percent in May. These orders often
are a barometer of business plans to expand and modernize and have
been a major source of economic strength in recent years.
</P>
<P>
Orders for military goods shot up 13.4 percent after plunging
11.9 percent in May. Excluding military goods, orders rose 1
percent.
</P>
<P>
Shipments, a measure of current activity, were up 0.9 percent,
also representing the second advance in three months.
</P>
<P>
Inventories rose 0.3 percent, the eleventh increase in 12
months. 
</P>
</TEXT>
