<HEADLINE> France to Close Military Base in Central Africa </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- France said it plans to close
one of its military bases in the Central Africa Republic and wane
down another, reports reaching here said today.
</P>
<P>
French Defense Minister Alain Richard made the announcement in
Bangui, capital of the Central Africa Republic at the end of the
tour of three African countries where some 3,000 French troops
are stationed.
</P>
<P>
In the Central Africa Republic, Alain Richard held talks with
President Ange Patassa. after that, reports said, Alain Richard
revealed that the Bouar base in the west region of the country
would close and forces at another military base in the nation's
capital Bangui would be reduced.
</P>
<P>
France has two military bases in Central Africa with some
1,400 soldiers. The bases were set up in accordance with the
defense agreement signed between the two countries.
</P>
<P>
The Bouar base has been used for many French military
operations in the central African region.
</P>
<P>
The French Defense Minister began his tour of three African
countries on July 29 which has taken him to Gabon, Chad and the
Central Africa Republic.
</P>
<P>
According to the reports, the French authorities had decided
last week to cut down the number of French troops stationed on
the African continent from 8,000 to 5,000. The cut will take
place first of all in Cote d'Ivoire, Gabon, Chad, the Central
Africa Republic and Djibouti. 
</P>
</TEXT>
