<HEADLINE> Ross will Visit Mideast before Albright </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said on
Friday that he will first send mediator Dennis Ross to the Middle
East before considering any visit by Secretary of State Madeleine
Albright to the region.
</P>
<P>
"I have said all along I will send the secretary of state to
the Middle East at the appropriate time. But I want Mr Ross to go
there to do the work I am sending him there to do, to get the
reaction of the leaders and then we will make a decision (on a
trip by Albright)," Clinton told reporters at the White House.
</P>
<P>
Ross has been scheduled the Middle East trip this weekend but
was postponed as a result of suicide bombings at a Jerusalem
market, which killed 15 people and injured more than 150.
</P>
<P>
Clinton said: "It was appropriate to delay that (trip) in view
of the terrible loss of life and the bombing. Then we will see
where we are."
</P>
<P>
"When the period of mourning is over I will send Dennis Ross to
the Middle East to meet with the leaders there with our latest
ideas," Clinton added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's Middle East advisory, including Secretary of State
Albright, National Security Advisor Sandy Berger and mediator
Ross, held a meeting on Thursday at the White House, making an
assessment of the situation following the bombings.
</P>
<P>
Reports said Albright was considering take her first trip to
the Middle East since she became the secretary of state.
</P>
<P>
State Department spokesman James Foley said the Israeli
mourning period was believed to last seven days. Asked if that
meant Ross would travel at the end of next week, Foley said: "I
would say that's in the ballpark."
</P>
<P>
With regard to Albright's travel, Foley said: "The secretary
will likely travel some time after that. I can't say when
precisely that would be because that will depend in part on the
results of Dennis's mission." 
</P>
</TEXT>
