<HEADLINE> Kenya to Go Along as IMF Loan Suspended </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Finance Minister Musalia
Mudavadi today said the government is committed to maintain
economic stability following the suspension of a loan to Kenya by
the International Monetary Fund (IMF).
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here today, he said that the
government would cut its expenditure for this year and take
sufficient revenue measures to safeguard the macro economic
stability.
</P>
<P>
"The government will initiate discussions with the IMF on a
possible economic 'shadow' program which does not involve
financial support from the IMF," said Mudavadi.
</P>
<P>
The Washington-based IMF today decided to suspend the Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility (ESAF) loan which was agreed upon
between the Kenyan government and the IMF in April last year.
</P>
<P>
The IMF alleged that the measures the Kenyan government was
prepared to take fell short of meeting the clearly expressed
concerns of IMF member countries in the area of governance.
</P>
<P>
Following the suspension, the local financial markets
witnessed an initial panic caused by short-term foreign "hot"
money.
</P>
<P>
Mudavadi conceded that "this could have serious repercussions.
It could dent investor confidence, affect the Shilling (Kenya's
currency), affect inflation and it is something that could shake
confidence in the economy."
</P>
<P>
In response to the IMF decision, Kenya's Central Bank Governor
Micah Cheserem also said that the IMF decision had seriously hurt
Kenya's credibility, and he called for taking urgent measures to
limit the damage.
</P>
<P>
The three-year ESAF loan totalling 205 million U.S. Dollars
was approved last year but payments were conditional on Kenya's
meeting promises on constitutional reform, which is believed to
be able to help bring democracy into the country.
</P>
<P>
The loan was to be disbursed in six half-yearly instalments of
36 million Dollars each. The first instalment was released on
May 16, last year and the second one was due last November but
was withheld for "unresolved issues". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
