<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Investors Urged to Calm Monetary Market in Kenya </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's business community today
urged all investors to act in solidarity to calm the local
financial markets in a bid to ensure economic stability.
</P>
<P>
The financial markets today witnessed an initial panic caused
by the decision of the International Monetary Fund (IMF) to
suspend a 205 million U.S. Dollars loan to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The IMF today decided to suspend the three-year Enhanced
Structural Adjustment Facility loan agreed on in April last year
between the Kenyan government and the IMF.
</P>
<P>
The suspension decision has had serious repercussions on the
financial markets in Nairobi.
</P>
<P>
A dealer of the Barclays Bank said today that "the Kenyan
Shilling opened at 59-59.50 versus the (U.S.) Dollar and then
depreciated to 60-62.50 within 20 minutes."
</P>
<P>
There were bids at as low as 64.50 for two leading commercial
banks but many banks were tied in the 60 to 63 band versus the
Dollar compared to around 59 at the close Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a press statement issued here today, the National Chamber
of Commerce and Industry, and the Kenya Association of
Manufacturers said that the initial panic was caused by
short-term foreign "hot" money.
</P>
<P>
The statement noted that the government should stamp out
corruption, reduce dependence on donor aid and aid-funded
projects.
</P>
<P>
It pointed out that Kenyans were capable of resolving their
problems internally and should not allow the economy to be ruined
by political squabbles. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
