<HEADLINE> S. Leone coup maker Tough as Talks Collapse </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
YAOUNDE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Talks held in Cote d'Ivoire
aimed at returning Sierra Leone to civilian rule broke down
following a defiant statement from the country's military leader
major Johny Koromah, Cameroun Tribune reported here today.
</P>
<P>
Koromah who led the coup on May 25 that ousted the
democratically elected President Tejan Kabbah said a hand-over of
power will take four years (1997 - 2001).
</P>
<P>
Koromah made the statement to national television and radio
stations, emphasizing that his government will not be stampeded
and were prepared to fight any aggression to the last drop of
their blood, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Ministers from the Economic Community of West African States
(ECOWAS), who have been mediating, accused the coup leaders of
coming to an earlier agreement to hand over power back to the
ousted President Kabbah. They called for the tightening of
sanctions.
</P>
<P>
But only hours after ECOWAS announced the tightening of
blockade on Sierra Leone, a ship with thousands of tons of rice
docked in the capital Freetown where crowds were said cheered its
arrival.
</P>
<P>
United Nations Security Council has expressed deep concerns
over the breakdown of the talks. 
</P>
</TEXT>
