<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Lifts Ban on Advanced Weapons Sales to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
today lifted a 20-year-old ban on the sale of advanced weapons to
Latin American nations.
</P>
<P>
"The president has decided to establish a process for
case-by-case consideration of requests for advanced arms transfers
to countries of that region," White House spokesman Michael
McCurry said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
The decision gives a green light to Chile, which is considering
buying as many as two dozen American F-16s to replace its own
aging fighters.
</P>
<P>
"This decision puts U.S. arms transfer policy toward Latin
America on a par with our policy toward other regions of the world
and will be implemented in a way that serves our objective of
promoting stability, restraint, and cooperation in the region,"
McCurry said.
</P>
<P>
Latin America has changed dramatically from a region dominated
by coups and military governments to civilian control in the past
ten years.
</P>
<P>
"Our partnership with countries in the region has reached a new
level of maturity, cooperation and dialogue," the spokesman added.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. has long regarded Latin America as its backyard. But
Europeans have eyed the region for potential markets in recent
years. The European Union had a bigger trade volume with Latin
America than the U.S. last year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
