<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0038 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe Launches Breast-feeding Week </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Zimbabwe today joined the
international community in launching the world breast-feeding
week, an initiative of the United Nations designed to encourage
maintenance of breast-feeding culture.
</P>
<P>
Health and Child Welfare Minister Timothy stamps said at the
launching ceremony that Zimbabwe continued to promote
breast-feeding despite international speculation on the safety of
doing so while a mother is HIV positive.
</P>
<P>
"There is no evidence yet that HIV virus which causes AIDS can
be transmitted through breast milk," Stamps said.
</P>
<P>
"Having reviewed the situation in the light of currently
available information on the risk of HIV transmission through
Breast milk, we are determined that there is no reason to change
the ministry's policy based on the 1992 world health
organization, UNICEF and unaids consensus," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said what is important was to protect women against the
risk of HIV infection prior to and during pregnancy, and during
the period of breast-feeding.
</P>
<P>
"HIV positive women should not embark on pregnancy,'' he said,
adding, ''human beings have a responsibility to stop the spread
of the virus.''
</P>
<P>
Breast milk was cheaper and could adequately nourish the baby
exclusively for the first six months, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
