<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Egypt: Mideast Situation Extremely Critical </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Egyptian Foreign Minister Amr
Moussa described the present situation in the Middle East as
"extremely critical and dangerous" due to a prolonged peace
deadlock caused by the Israeli settlement policy.
</P>
<P>
"With the recent violent operations, the situation has reached
a stage that dictates the immediate exertion of intensive efforts
in the real sense of the words to contain it," Moussa told
reporters in Alexandria, the Egyptian second largest city.
</P>
<P>
Emerging from a meeting between Egyptian President Hosni
Mubarak and Palestinian National Authority (PNA) President Yasser
Arafat in Alexandria, Moussa said that there is severe tension
between the Palestinian and Israeli sides.
</P>
<P>
"The problem is not simple," he said, calling for the revival
of negotiations together with "the elements of the peace process
as set down in the Madrid and Oslo accords."
</P>
<P>
Moussa said that Arafat is strongly convinced that the PNA
could not be held responsible for what has happened as
investigations into the suicide bombing attack in Jerusalem have
not so far led to results while there are Israeli mass punishments
against the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, the explosion in a foodstuff market in Jewish
West Jerusalem killed 14 people, including the two suicide
bombers, and wounded 150 others.
</P>
<P>
Egyptian contacts will be sustained especially with the
Palestinian side with the aim of breaking the deadlock in the
peace process, he said.
</P>
<P>
The Egyptian foreign minister also promised all-out efforts by
Egypt to ease the sufferings of the Palestinian people and salvage
the peace process.
</P>
<P>
He expressed hope that the U.S. initiative would be launched as
soon as possible and would be balanced and based on various
considerations that bring the two parties back to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
"The initiative is an American and not an American-Egyptian
one," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Moussa said U.S. Secretary of State Madeleine Albright made a
"good and required" statement by saying Wednesday she was working
to renew U.S. aid to Palestinians despite the bombing of a Jewish
market and continued concerns about Arafat's commitment to
Israel's security.
</P>
<P>
"Statements by Albright and U.S. President Bill Clinton point
out that the situation is grave and that the two parties should
honor their obligations," he said.
</P>
<P>
"This is a balanced principle and a proper prelude to the
American initiative," he added.
</P>
<P>
Clinton urged restraint on both sides after the suicide bombing
attacks and said he would first send his envoy Dennis Ross to the
region before a visit by Albright.
</P>
<P>
On Israel's threats to re-occupy the Palestinian lands, Moussa
ruled out that Israel would carry out those threats.
</P>
<P>
He described the recent Jerusalem incident as "an addition to
Israeli considerations that harm the Palestinian side," referring
to recent punishments endorsed by the Israeli cabinet against the
Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Israel immediately imposed a closure on the West Bank and Gaza
Strip after the incident, barring tens of thousands of
Palestinians from jobs in Israel.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
