<HEADLINE> Nanjing's Cultural Exchanges with Israel </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A recent photo show on the
Holocaust of World War II brought many visitors to Nanjing, where
Japanese invaders massacred hundreds of thousands of residents in
1937.
</P>
<P>
The exhibit is just one of the many cultural exchanges that
have taken place between eastern coastal Jiangsu Province and
Israel in the past few years, said Ji Genzhang, director of the
provincial Department of Culture.
</P>
<P>
In February, 1995, the department and the Israeli consulate
general in Shanghai co-sponsored a photo exhibition on daily life
in modern-day Israel. Israeli Consul General to Shanghai attended
the opening ceremony and said that he hoped more cultural
exchanges would take place between his homeland and
economically-developed Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
Later that year, Jiangsu chose over 20 children's paintings for
an international competition at the invitation of the Israeli
foreign ministry and a cultural foundation.
</P>
<P>
A photo show on the late Israeli Prime Minister Yitzhak Rabin's
diplomatic activities was held in November, 1996.
</P>
<P>
And the Nanjing Artists Ensemble took part in the 11th
International Folk Dance Festival held in Tel Aviv in 1996.
</P>
