<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ribeiro, the Golden Girl of Portugal </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Fernanda Ribeiro was seven years
old when her father offered her the first pair of running shoes,
and took her to a tiny village in northern Portugal where she had
her debut training.
</P>
<P>
Now, at 26, the gifted runner has conquered nearly all world
titles and looks set to defend her crown in the women's 10,000
meters at the current 6th World Athletics Championships.
</P>
<P>
The defending champion and Olympic winner said here today after
the qualifying race:"I believe I am in a very good form. Before I
went to Sweden at the previous meet, I promised my mother that I
would be back with a gold medal. I made it - one gold and one
silver. Before Atlanta Games it was the same story. I'm looking
forward to do it again, right here in Athens."
</P>
<P>
Ribeiro had being asked, in her earlier days, if she'd like to
become Rosa Mota or Aurora Cunha, her former distance running
idols. Ribeiro replied: "No, I want to be even better and more
successful then they are."
</P>
<P>
She told the press a small story. When she was a small kid, she
was on the way to the training ground with her father, who used to
take her on his motorbike. It was raining hard, they fell down on
the slippery road and she injured herself pretty bad.
</P>
<P>
Covered with blood and full of pain, she had only one thing in
mind - not missing the training sesion. Her father forced her to
take a break, but she didn't.
</P>
<P>
"I am that kind of person. I have seven lives, like cats
do. Last year, I was injured for two months before the Olympics,
and only God knows what I've been through to make it there," said
Ribeiro.
</P>
<P>
After all her success she never changed, and nothing can get
her out of the track.
</P>
<P>
In one of her darkest moments - due to an injury - she promised
to walk from Oporto to Fatima (about 200 kilometers) in case she'd
win a gold medal in Atlanta. She did so, and fulfilled her
promise, walking down to Fatima in two days.
</P>
<P>
"I believe God is always by my side, giving me strength to run
and win. When I go to the starting line, I pray and ask our Holy
Lady from Fatima to protect me," revealed Ribeiro. "This time, I
will run the race with the same shoes I used at the previous
championships," she added.
</P>
<P>
Ribeiro qualified for the 10,000m finals with ease, but she
will face some challenge posed by Derartu Tulu of Ethiopia, the
1992 Olympic champion, Tegla Loroupe of Kenya, bronze medal winner
at last championships, and Elana Meyer of South Africa, 1994 World
Cup winner.
</P>
<P>
With China's world record holder Wang Junxia pulled out of the
meet, Ribeiro fears nobody, but she admitted that Wang's record is
well beyond her reach this time. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
