<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Arafat Accuses Israel for Tough Measures on </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat today accused Israel of having virtually
declared a war upon the Palestinians by toughening security
measures on them.
</P>
<P>
After a meeting this morning with Egyptian Leader Hosni Mubarak
in the Mediterranean city of Alexandria, Arafat also urged
immediate international intervention to prevent escalation of
violence.
</P>
<P>
Describing his talks with Mubarak as "important, useful and
constructive," Arafat told reporters that he briefed the Egyptian
leader on the serious measures taken by the Israeli government
following Wednesday's suicide bombings in Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The bombings carried out by two Palestinian extremists in a
crowded market killed 14 people and injured 150 others. They are
the deadliest attack against Israelis since March 1996.
</P>
<P>
"Despite the Palestinian condemnation of the incident, the
Israeli government took advantage of the situation to launch a war
against the Palestinians, the Palestinian National Authority and
its leaders," he added.
</P>
<P>
He said the Israelis should fight terrorism instead of picking
a quarrel with the Palestinians and taking such serious measures
as closing the Palestinian international crossing-points with
Egypt and Jordan.
</P>
<P>
"The crossing-points should never have been closed," Arafat
said, adding that Israel has suspended the transfer of Palestinian
tax and customs revenues to the Palestinian coffers.
</P>
<P>
Israel immediately imposed a closure on the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, barring tens of thousands of Palestinians from jobs in
Israel. The closure was tougher than usual, restricting even
Palestinians' movements between their autonomous West Bank towns.
</P>
<P>
Protesting the Israeli "mass-punitive measures which have
exceeded all logical limits," he added, however, what is going on
is part of the serious siege imposed on the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
"This has always been the target of the Israeli government and
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu," Arafat said, warning anew of
the Israeli government's plans to strike at the peace march and
evade the implementation of Palestinian-Israeli agreements.
</P>
<P>
U.S. President Bill Clinton's intervention is needed at this
phase more than ever before, Arafat said, noting that the
agreements sponsored by both the U.S. and Russia, have to be
rescued.
</P>
<P>
"Israel's faith in the importance of the peace process is the
only way to escape the current peace crisis," he added.
</P>
<P>
Egypt has promised to take action on the various tracks to ease
the sufferings of the Palestinian people, according to the
Palestinian leader.
</P>
<P>
On Friday night, Arafat called for holding an Arab League
extraordinary session to adopt a unified Arab stance in the face
of the Israeli practices against the Palestinian people and the
Mideast process. 
</P>
</TEXT>
