<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Soldiers Beat Foreign Journalists in </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli soldiers again
fiercely attacked and beat foreign journalists in the west city of
Hebron this morning, according to a report of JMCC, a Palestinian
press service based in East Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The incident took place when the reporters were filming
soldiers refusing Palestinian doctors and residents to enter
Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Soldiers arrested a Al-Hayat Al-Jadihah reporter, beat and
injured a Reuters cameraman before arresting him. The report did
not give their names.
</P>
<P>
Similar incidents also took place in other West Bank
checkpoints. Journalists were harrassed and TV crew men were
prevented from filming checkpoints.
</P>
<P>
Palestinians working with foreign press were even barred from
passing through checkpoints although they hold valid press cards
issued by the Israeli Government Press Office.
</P>
<P>
Israeli soldiers quarreled with MBC TV (Middle East
Broadcasting Corporation, regional) crew at the northern Gaza
checkpoint, barred them from traveling to Jericho and threatened
to confiscate their camera cassettes after they filmed the
checkpoint.
</P>
<P>
Also in Hebron on July 13, five foreign journalists were
wounded by live ammunition or rubber bullets when they covered
clashes between Palestinian teenage stone-throwers and heavily
armed Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Press Association lodged a complaint to the Israel
Defense Forces (IDF) about the incident.
</P>
<P>
Last week, soldiers even involved themselves in a diplomatic
incident. A Jordanian diplomat was detained at an army roadblock
near Maccabim between Jerusalem and Tel Aviv for five hours. His
car was searched despite its diplomatic plate.
</P>
<P>
The Jordanian Foreign Ministry has presented an official
complaint to Israeli ambassador to Amman Oded Eran, saying that
the diplomat was insulted by the soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Chief of Staff Lt.-Gen. Amnon Lipkin-Shahak has
criticized the troops for the incident, according to a report of
the state-run Israel Radio today. 
</P>
</TEXT>
