<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Shanghai Sets Targets for New Round of Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai, China's largest
industrial city, has worked out an outline for a new round of
economic development projects to turn itself into an international
economic, trade and financial center.
</P>
<P>
According to official sources, Shanghai's per-capita Gross
Domestic Product (GDP) is expected to top 3,000 US dollars this
year.
</P>
<P>
Xiao Lin, deputy director of the Economic Department under the
Shanghai Planning Commission, told participants at an
international workshop on development strategy that with this goal
realized, Shanghai would enter a new phase of economic growth.
</P>
<P>
A new target has already been set: The city will try to raise
the annual per-capita GDP up to 5,000 US dollars by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
One of the key measures is to increase the share of the service
sector in the city's total GDP to 48 percent by the end of this
century from the present 42 percent. The service industry mainly
covers financial service, chain stores, entrepot trade, shipping,
tourism and information service.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai will give priority to developing industries of
automotive manufacturing, electronic telecommunication, electronic
and machinery industry, biological engineering, new materials and
environmental protection, which is expected to take 56 percent of
the city's total industrial output.
</P>
<P>
The official said Shanghai is likely to maintain a sustained
economic growth for the next 10 years, with its growth rate two
percentage points higher than that of the country's average.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
