<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Guangzhou's Consumer Goods Market Brisk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Guangzhou, capital of south
China's Guangdong Province, has reported retail sales of 38.233
billion yuan-worth of goods in the first half of this year.
</P>
<P>
According to local sources, the figure represents a rise of
15.75 percent in a year-on-year comparison, and an increase of 1.6
percentage points over the national growth rate in retail sales.
</P>
<P>
Since the beginning of this year, prices for major consumer
goods such as cereal, edible oil, foodstuffs, meat, vegetables and
eggs have remained stable.
</P>
<P>
The retail price index of goods for the January-June period
dropped by 6.7 percentage points, while sales of 12 major items
have increased by more than 20 percent.
</P>
<P>
Observers say that the success of the macro-economic control
and the startup of new economic powerhouses are mostly responsible
for the stable market prices.
</P>
<P>
The provincial capital chalked up 73.771 billion yuan in GDP
(gross domestic product) in the period, a rise of 13 percent. The
comprehensive economic benefit index was 119.16 percent, up 5.8
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
In the meantime, an upswing in exports has helped to alleviate
the situation of supply exceeding demand found in certain
commodities.
</P>
<P>
Customs statistics show that Guangzhou exported 4.765 billion
US dollars-worth of goods in the first half of this year,
up 26.36 percent.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
