<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0069 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Tehran Mayor Counter-Attacks Conservative Camp </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Tehran's liberal Mayor
Gholamhossein Karbaschi termed today the recent arrests of his
deputies as "a revenge" by the conservative camp for their defeat
in presidential elections.
</P>
<P>
The mayor made the remark at a press conference. This was his
first reaction to the arrests of his seven deputies who were
apprehended on July 27.
</P>
<P>
However, Karbaschi did not specify any person or group for the
criticism.
</P>
<P>
"The same group (conservative right) which was defeated in the
elections is behind these activities," the mayor said.
</P>
<P>
He attacked the rightists for breaking the law by sending armed
plain-clothes men to arrest his deputies without informing him in
advance.
</P>
<P>
"A certain armed forces called 'Justice Ministry's Security'
have committed illegal acts ... They arrested a group of people,
detained them and mistreated them in the municipal building," he
said.
</P>
<P>
The timing of the arrests showed that they were politically
motivated and were meant to put pressure on president-elect
Khatami who will be sworn in at the Iranian Parliament on August
4, he added.
</P>
<P>
Karbaschi served as the ideologue of the liberal camp known
as G-6 that has supported the economic development policies of
Iran's outgoing President Akbar Hashemi Rafsanjani.
</P>
<P>
During the presidential campaign of Mohammad Khatami,
Karbaschi served as one of his strategists. Khatami won over 20
million votes, or 69 percent of the total votes on May 23,
defeating his main conservative rival Parliament Speaker Ali
Akbar Nateq-Nouri, who has been backed by Iranian Supreme Leader
Ali Khamenei.
</P>
<P>
Observers here noted Iranian Supreme Leader Khamenei has
launched the nationwide anti-corruption campaign last month
against the outgoing government headed by President Akbar Hashemi
Rafsanjani, who will officially step down Monday.
</P>
<P>
The 64-year-old president, his family members and his some
cabinet members have been under constant attacks by hardliners
for various kinds of corruption since the beginning of 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
