<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya Publishes Law Amendment Bill </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Kenyan Attorney General Amos
Wako Friday published the Statute Law Bill 1997 which seeks the
repeal and amendment of certain laws, local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
He said that in drafting the Bill, the government endeavored
to take into consideration the draft Bill put forward by the
National Convention Executive Council, an umbrella body of
Kenya's opposition parties.
</P>
<P>
The repeal and amendment of some laws will enhance the
enjoyment of human rights by all Kenyans and facilitate the
freedom of assembly and expression in the country, Wako noted.
</P>
<P>
The Bill seeks, among other things, to establish an
anti-corruption authority with more powers to combat corruption
in the public services.
</P>
<P>
Western donors said that corruption is their major complaint
against the Kenyan government, adding that the losses from
mismanagement and corruption are greater than aid donations in
1992 and 1993.
</P>
<P>
The International Monetary Fund Friday stopped a three-year
aid program to Kenya amounting to 215 million U.S Dollars for an
alleged government failure to show its commitment to fighting
corruption, according to a "East African Standard" report today.
</P>
<P>
In 1991 and 1992, the Kenyan government paid some 100 million
Dollars to a company, calling Goldenberg International, under a
gold and diamond export compensation scheme.
</P>
<P>
However, the paper said, the problem is that Kenya produces
little gold and no diamonds deposits.
</P>
<P>
Owner of the Goldenberg and four former government officials,
who involved in the scandal were charged with defrauding the
government in 1993, but the Kenya High Court
ended its prosecution in June this year after four years of
delay.
</P>
<P>
The paper quoted one diplomat as saying that "what donors want
are practical steps in dealing with the Goldenberg culprits."
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
