<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Typhoon Victor Severely Affects Hong Kong Transport </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Typhoon Victor, which is
expected to land very close to Hong Kong late this evening, has
brought to a halt most transport services in the Special
Administrative Region (SAR) this weekend.
</P>
<P>
The Hong Kong Observatory has already upgraded the typhoon
signal from No 8 to No 9 as the tropical cyclone, centered about
70 km south of Hong Kong at 6 p.m. today, is moving north at 18 km
per hour towards the Pearl River Estuary.
</P>
<P>
At Hong Kong International Airport, 51 flight arrivals have
been diverted or delayed with ten scheduled arrivals canceled. A
total of 48 departure flights have been suspended.
</P>
<P>
Underground railway started to operate at longer intervals at
noon, and Kowloon-Canton Railway warned that services might be
suspended anytime from 7 p.m.
</P>
<P>
The Peak Tram, a cable-hauled funicular railway which scales
along the subtropical hill from downtown Central up to the
Victoria Peak, suspended its services in the afternoon, so did
trams running on the north coast of Hong Kong Island. Bus and
seaborne services have all come to a stop.
</P>
<P>
The Government Information Services said that there were 32
reports of collapsed trees, but no reports of injuries. There were
several reports of flooding and dangerous scaffolding, signboards
or concrete plastic falls.
</P>
<P>
The Home Affairs Department has opened 37 temporary shelters in
various districts and so far provided help to 152 people in need
of shelter during the bad weather. 
</P>
</TEXT>
