<HEADLINE> Barnes out of Men's Shot Put Final </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- World record holder and Olympic
champion Randy Barnes of the United States failed to qualify for
the men's shot put final here Saturday morning at the 6th World
Athletics Championships.
</P>
<P>
The pre-race hot favourite, who popped the year's best 22.03
meters in June, made a sensational upset in the qualifying
round. He opened a 19.23 and improved to 19.51 next round before
fouling the last throw. The poor result placed him 14th in the
qualifying round.
</P>
<P>
Defending champion John Godina of the United States was the
only man who hit the ball over the 21-meter line. Godina was
beaten by Barnes in the last round at last year's Olympics, and he
finished fourth at the U.S. Trials, but the IAAF gave him a chance
to defend the title with a wild card.
</P>
<P>
In the afternoon's final, not to be discounted is Finland's
Mika Halvari, who won the silver at the last championships and has
strongly recovered from the ruptured Achilles tendon that ruined
his Olympic hopes last year.
</P>
<P>
Three others with the ability to challenge Godina for the gold
include Aleksandr Bagach of the Ukraine, who has thrown a lifetime
best of 21.47 this season, and remaining Americans Kevin Toth
(21.78) and C.J. Hunter(21.34), both of whom hit their personal
bests at the USA Championships this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
