<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN's Services Trade Might Be Freed by Two Steps </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Members of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN) will be allowed to liberalize
their services trades by two deadlines according to their
preparedness, a senior Thai official said.
</P>
<P>
Those members who are well placed for competition will be fully
liberalized by 2010, said Charin Harnsuebsai, deputy
director-general of the Business Economics Department of the Thai
Commerce Ministry.
</P>
<P>
Those members in a weaker position, or who want to protect the
sector for a longer period, will complete the process by 2020,
Charin was quoted as saying by local media today.
</P>
<P>
The new approach was proposed by Singapore and a working group
of ASEAN will submit related plans to the annual meeting of
ASEAN's economic ministers scheduled for October this year in
Kuala Lumpur.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN agreed to free trade in telecommunications, transport,
finance services, tourism and business services in December 1995
and negotiations concerned are scheduled for completion by 1999.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN now consists of nine members - Brunei, Indonesia, Laos,
Malaysia, Myanmar, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand and
Vietnam.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
