<BODY>
<HEADLINE> HK to Provide Services for Youths at Risk </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Following two separate
researches, two types of services have been recommended as
measures to tackle the problems of young people at risk and
prevent juvenile crime, a spokesman for the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) said today.
</P>
<P>
The Standing Committee on Young Offenders (SCOYO) of the Fight
Crime Committee (FCC) has recently studied the findings of the
researches on "Juvenile Gangs and Runaway Youths" and the
"Effectiveness of Rehabilitation Programs for Young Offenders".
</P>
<P>
The first research recommends a pilot scheme for the setting up
of "youth mobile teams" to cater for those young people who hang
out at night and may be exposed to various bad influences.
</P>
<P>
Under the scheme, which will commence later this year and will
operate from 11 pm to 6 am, social workers would work to prevent
the so-called young night-drifters from falling prey to
undesirable elements or breaking the law.
</P>
<P>
The second research recommends the continuation of a pilot
scheme which has been proved effective.
</P>
<P>
The scheme, which serves young people put on Probation Order or
School Order and those cautioned under the Police Superintendents'
Discretion Scheme, provides structured programs and intensively
supervised activities for youths to reintegrate themselves into
mainstream education or workforce and thus minimizing the
likelihood of their turning to crime.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
