<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0100 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British PM Names Lords to Take on Tory Majority </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, August 2 (Xinhua) -- British Prime Minister Tony Blair
named 57 new peers today, the largest number of peers appointed in
a single announcement in modern times.
</P>
<P>
In the long list, 31 are Labor Lords as Blair begins his
attempt to reverse the inbuilt Conservative domination of the
upper House of Lords. The Conservatives had managed to stay in
power over the past 18 years until the May election.
</P>
<P>
The new Labor peers will boost the party's representation in
the Lords to 157, but the Conservatives, with 494 adherents, will
still be in a massive majority.
</P>
<P>
The list of new Labor peers was dominated by former MPs but
several industrialists, businessmen and writers were also elevated.
</P>
<P>
The new contingent of peers provides consolation for several
senior Tories who lost their seats in the election and a lease of
life for many Labor MPs who stood down before Labor regained power
three months ago.
</P>
<P>
The House of Lords is far less powerful than the lower House of
Commons, but still has the power to delay non-financial
legislation from becoming law.
</P>
<P>
During the election campaign, Labor pledged to end the right of
hereditary peers, some holding titles dating back to medieval
times, to sit in the House of Lords.
</P>
<P>
This would leave it largely in the hands of "life peers," such
as those Blair named today, whose titles are not inherited by
their children. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
