<HEADLINE> Bangladeshi Garment Workers Under Insurance Scheme </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh's garment manufacturers
have agreed to bring a total of 1.3 million workers of the
garments industry under insurance scheme following two tragic
garment factory incidents within half a month here.
</P>
<P>
Each worker will be eligible for a 40,000 taka (about 920 U.S.
dollars) compensation claim under the insurance scheme, according
to a press release published today by the Bangladesh Garment
Manufacturers and Exporters Association (BGMEA).
</P>
<P>
The BGMEA also pledged a number of steps to stop recurrence of
incidents of fire and stampede in garments factories.
</P>
<P>
On July 30, 26 garment workers died in a stampede in a factory
in Dhaka. Another factory fire also claimed nine lives on July 16
while many more lost their lives in such incidents earlier.
</P>
<P>
The BGMEA said that some other precautionary measures will be
taken within the next 30 days in all garment factories. These will
include building alternate staircase, installation of fire
extinguishing equipment and other emergency safety systems.
</P>
<P>
To implement the steps, 15 teams of the BGMEA will start their
monitoring work within three days, the press release added.
</P>
</TEXT>
