<HEADLINE> President Moi Emboldens Kenyans as IMF Loan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Facing a currency depreciation
after International Monetary Fund decided to suspend its loan to
the country, Kenyan President Daniel arap Moi called the
countrymen to be confident in holding their own destiny.
</P>
<P>
Moi said that his government would not succumb to threats,
intimidations or ultimatums, the "Kenya Times" reported today.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a graduation ceremony held by Kenya Forestry
College in Kericho District, western Kenya, he said that Kenyans
should be allowed to decide their political own destiny. The
fruits of democracy could not be realized if the country was to
embrace tribalism at the expense of national cohesion, he added.
</P>
<P>
The Kenyan Head of State made the remarks following a decision
taken yesterday by the International Monetary fund to suspend its
215 million U.S. Dollars three-year loan to Kenya.
</P>
<P>
President Moi thanked the German government for its continued
development support to Kenya, especially the Kenya Forestry
College.
</P>
<P>
On the same occasion, Michael Gerdts, German Ambassador to
Kenya, noted that President Moi had offered a number of
significant proposals and in doing so had extended an invitation
for dialogue to all political parties in the country.
</P>
<P>
The envoy said time had come for all groups in the East
African country to join in dialogue and present their views and
proposals as part of their contribution to the future destiny of
the country.
</P>
<P>
Only in a co-operative effort by all Kenyans, could unity of
the Kenyan people be preserved and a successful and prosperous
future of Kenya be assured, he added. 
</P>
