<HEADLINE> Arafat Arrives in Egypt for Talks with Mubarak </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat flew today to Alexandria, the second
largest city of Egypt, to discuss with Egyptian leader Hosni
Mubarak the latest development after two suicide bombings in
Jerusalem.
</P>
<P>
The meeting took place three days after the two bombing attacks
which killed 15 people and injured 170 others.
</P>
<P>
The summit, the third in ten days, comes within the framework
of coordination and consultations between the Egyptian and
Palestinian leaders, Arafat's advisor Nabil Abu Rdein, who is
accompanying him on the trip, was quoted by Egyptian news agency
MENA as saying.
</P>
<P>
The Arafat-Mubarak summit will also cover the situation in the
region in light of measures adopted by the Israeli government
against the Palestinian people.
</P>
<P>
Arafat Friday night received a phone call from Egyptian
Foreign Minister Amr Moussa on the political situation in the
region and the worsening deadlock stifling the PNA-Israeli
negotiations.
</P>
<P>
He briefed Egypt's top diplomat on the negative consequences
of the Israeli army blockade of Palestinian self-rule areas as
part of a collective punitive policy against the Palestinian
people.
</P>
<P>
After Wednesday's bombings, Israel suspended peace talks with
the PNA, imposed a total closure on the West Bank and Gaza Strip
and threatened to reenter Palestinian-ruled areas to arrest
militants if Arafat failed to act.
</P>
<P>
Arafat Friday night called for holding an Arab League
extraordinary session to adopt a unified Arab stance in the face
of the Israeli practices against the Palestinian people and the
Mideast process.
</P>
<P>
The two deadly bombings, for which the Islamic Resistance
Movement has claimed responsibility, shattered renewed hope for a
possible breakthrough in the Palestinian-Israeli peace process
just days after the two sides agreed to resume talks that have
been frozen for four months. 
</P>
