<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Man Pulled Alive From Collapsed Ski Lodge in Australia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Rescue workers have pulled a man
alive from under one of the two collapsed ski lodges destroyed by
a landslide two days ago at the Thredbo ski resort near Canberra.
</P>
<P>
Stuart Diver, 27, was pulled from the wreckage of the lodges
this evening, more than 64 hours after the landslide, with
multiple lacerations, local media reported.
</P>
<P>
Ambulance Service Superintendent Allan Dent said Diver, who had
no shoes on his feet when rescued, was in a serious but stable
condition.
</P>
<P>
Twenty people were believed to be trapped in the wreckage in
the disaster, which occurred in the early hours of Thursday. Their
relatives have been told by police to expect the worst since then,
and six bodies have been uncovered from the ruins by about 400
rescue workers.
</P>
<P>
Police said paramedics of a special casualty access team first
made physical contact with Diver by punching a 10 centimeter hole
through the rubble early this morning.
</P>
<P>
One of the paramedics held hands with Diver and handed him a
torch so he could describe to rescue workers the debris
surrounding him.
</P>
<P>
Paramedics pumped hot air via a tube into the cavity where he
was trapped to keep him warm and fed him warm electrolyte fluids.
</P>
<P>
A police spokeswoman said it was believed that Diver was buried
beneath three concrete slabs with a fourth underneath him.
</P>
<P>
Diver, who was staying in the Bimbadeen ski lodge with his wife
Sally, was a supervising ski instructor and volunteer fireman at
the Snowy Mountains resort, which is 150 kilometers southeast of
Canberra.
</P>
<P>
He was stabilized by paramedics and specialist trauma surgeons
before being placed in the helicopter's "virtual flying intensive
care ward" and airlifted to a Canberra hospital for treatment.
</P>
<P>
Police Superintendent Charlie Sanderson told reporters at a
press conference today that a "miracle has occurred."
</P>
<P>
Sanderson said the breakthrough came at 05:37 this morning
(local time) when rescue workers made what had become a routine
probe of the rubble with listening devices. Signs of life were
detected when muffled sounds from under the slab were heard.
</P>
<P>
The temperatures in the ski resort plunged well below freezing
point for the fourth successive night.
</P>
<P>
Among those believed trapped in the rubble are Mim Sodergren
and Mike Sodergren, ski instructors from the United States, and
New Zealand-born ski instructor Mary Phillips. Most of the other
unidentified missing people are believed to be Australians working
for the ski resort. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
