<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0830 GMT, August 2 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Sixteen of the 18-member Palestinian cabinet have
submitted their resignation to President Yasser Arafat over
alleged corruption and mismanagement of funds, JMCC, a Palestinian
press service based in East Jerusalem, reported Saturday. It is
not yet clear whether Arafat accepts the resignation of so many
ministers. He is scheduled to fly to Cairo Saturday for talks with
Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak over the situation following the
two suicide bombings in Jerusalem Wednesday, killing 15 people and
wounding over 170 others.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton held talks on Friday
with Azerbaijan's President Heydar Aliyer at the White House and
both leaders agreed that it was important to expand the
partnership between the two countries through strengthening
bilateral cooperation in the political, security, economic and
commercial spheres.
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- President Bill Clinton said on Friday that he
will first send mediator Dennis Ross to the Middle East before
considering any visit by Secretary of State Madeleine Albright to
the region. Ross has been scheduled the Middle East trip this
weekend but was postponed as a result of suicide bombings at a
Jerusalem market on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
YAOUNDE -- France said it plans to close one of its military
bases in the Central Africa Republic and wane down another,
reports reaching here said Friday. Defense Minister Alain Richard
made the announcement in Bangui, capital of the Central Africa
Republic at the end of the tour of three African countries where
some 3,000 French troops are stationed. 
</P>
