<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Wild Animals Kill 115 People in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- A total of 115 people were
killed and 135 others injured by wild animals in Tanzania during
the year 1996/97 after the drought, which hit most parts of the
country, made the animals invade human settlements.
</P>
<P>
Tanzanian Minister for Natural Resources and Tourism, Zakia
Meghji, told the National Assembly in Dodoma Friday that a total
of 285 cows, 316 goats, 155 sheep and 133 other animals were also
eaten by the beasts.
</P>
<P>
Meghji said the droungt made the animals invade human
settlements where they also destroyed 51,660 acres of different
crops.
</P>
<P>
In combating the destructive animals, the ministry issued
3,140 rounds of ammunition and a number of lions, leopards,
elephants, hippos and other animals were killed in different
parts of the country by game wardens in collabroation with
villagers, Meghji said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the minister said during the anti-poaching exercise
during the last fiscal year, 2,383 kilograms of elephant tusks
worth about 215,000 US Dollars and 70 pieces of hippo teeth worth
about 580 US Dollars were recovered.
</P>
<P>
Surveillance is being maintained in all national parks and
game reserves to combat poaching, the minister added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
