<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 08:49 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran, Syria Call for End Israeli Occupation of </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Iran and Syria issued here Friday
night a joint statement, calling for an end to the Israeli
occupation of all Arab lands, Iran's official news agency IRNA
reported today.
</P>
<P>
The joint statement issued at the end of a 24-hour unexpected
visit to Iran by Syrian President Hafez al-Assad urged Israel to
return the Golan Heights, south Lebanon and Palestinian
territories to Arab countries.
</P>
<P>
Iran "vehemently supports the Syrian reasonable stance
demanding the return of Golan Heights to that country," said the
statement.
</P>
<P>
The two countries also expressed concern over the recent
military and security cooperation between Turkey and the Israeli
regime, according to the statement.
</P>
<P>
Calling the cooperation contradictory to the declaration of the
Organization of the Islamic Conference (OIC), Iran and Syria
called on Turkey to review its stance toward cooperation with
Israel.
</P>
<P>
The statement also stressed the two countries' support for
territorial integrity of Iraq as well as the struggle by the
Lebanese Islamic and national forces to liberate the territories
occupied by Israel.
</P>
<P>
It said the Israeli efforts to participate in the economic
cooperations in the region is a prelude to expand its influence in
Arab and Islamic countries and called for Islamic countries'
comprehensive sanctions against the Israeli regime.
</P>
<P>
The statement condemned the U.S. congress' decision to transfer
its embassy to Jerusalem, calling it "an antagonistic move against
Muslim nations" and an violation of all the relevant
U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
Iran and Syria also called on the world community to confront
the Israeli regime's recent desecration of Islamic and Christian
sanctities, which the statement termed as "a racial and criminal
act" by the Israeli government.
</P>
<P>
Al-Assad arrived in Tehran on July 31 amid reports that Syria,
Iran and Iraq had been trying to set up a joint block in
confrontation with the Israeli-Turkish close military cooperation.
</P>
<P>
He met with and had talks with all Iranian top leaders, but no
details have been reported about their efforts in forming the
block though they did discussed the "Iraqi issue". 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
