<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Fresh Fighting Erupts in S. Leone as Talks Break </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Fresh fighting has broken out in
Sierra Leone when traditional hunters known as Kamajures went
on the rampage, according to a report reaching here today.
</P>
<P>
The Kamajures attacked the fighters of ex-rebel Revolutionary
United Front and soldiers of the ruling Armed Forces Revolutionary
Council on Friday as the country's peace process suffered setback.
</P>
<P>
Fighting erupted in the eastern town of Ningi when one of the
Kamajure leaders, apparently responding to the breakdown in peace
talks between the military administration and its neighbors,
ordered his men to attack, the report said.
</P>
<P>
The peace talks, the second round held in Abidjan, Cote d'Ivoire,
collapsed in session immediately after Sierra Leone's military ruler
announced a four-year transition program on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A Kamajure leader, simply identified as Norman, was quoted as
saying that his forces "were now fighting because the junta in
Freetown has refused to accepted that peace is better for the people
of Sierra Leone."
</P>
<P>
"We have no choice than fight and bring back democracy and
reinstate the government of Ahmed Tejan Kabbah," he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Norman stated his men would create a safe passage
for returning civilians who had fled the country in the wake of
the May 25 coup.
</P>
<P>
People have begun to trickle back into the areas after they fled
into the Liberian border town nearby to avoid further clashes.
</P>
<P>
The breakdown of the peace talks triggered "deep concern" of the
United Nations Security Council and incurred condemnation from the
Commonwealth which suspended Sierra Leone's membership last month.
</P>
<P>
The Economic Community of West African States (ECOWAS) is to
tighten economic blockade and embargo against Sierra Leone. And the
possible use of force in order to restore the ousted civilian
government has also been announced.
</P>
<P>
Earlier report said the blockade by the west African
peacekeeping force known as ECOMOG has resulted in short supply
of foodstuffs, drugs, fuel and other daily necessities in the
war-torn country.
</P>
<P>
Despite the grim picture, a ship loaded with thousands of tons
of rice was reported to dock in Freetown on Friday, raising fears
of the effectiveness of the ECOMOG blockade.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
