<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Lebanese Favor Pirated Cables TV Service </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Lebanese television viewers are
switching to pirated satellite channels following a cabinet
decision to shut down unlicensed audio-visual stations, Beirut's
newspaper the Daily Star reported this morning.
</P>
<P>
The report said one week after the cabinet decision to close
unlicensed audio-visual media, more and more people began to flock
into the illegal cable market.
</P>
<P>
A supplier who wished to be anonymous, said that in the past
week alone, there had been 15 percent rise in subscription to his
illegal service which provides customers with a cable-supplied
array of channels at a fraction of the price of the satellite dish.
</P>
<P>
Satellite companies, on the other hand, have not experienced
any growth in sales since government's closure to unlicensed
audio-visual stations.
</P>
<P>
They estimated that at least 70 percent of the potential
satellite market has gone to illegal cable companies.
</P>
<P>
"The ratio of illegal to legal consumers is 70 to 30. The
potential loss of sales is a combination of the unregulated
existence of illegal suppliers and the country's economic
status," said Tony Hayek, a leading satellite supplier. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
