<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 07:11 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israel Vows to Arrest Palestinian Police Chief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Israeli Defense Minister
Yitzhak Mordechai has vowed to arrest Palestinian police chief
Ghazi Jabali on charges of plotting anti-Israeli terrorism.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to Israeli state television Friday night, Mordechai
said that Israel had concrete evidence to prove that Jabali had
ordered the planned attack against a Jewish settlement near
Nablus last month.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai was referring to the arrest of three Palestinian
policemen who were captured by Israeli soldiers on July 14 on
their way to carry out the attack. Israel has since been
demanding the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) arrest Jabali
and put him on trial.
</P>
<P>
Following Wednesday's two suicide bombings in Jerusalem's
Mahane Yehuda market which killed 15 people and wounded 170
others, the Israeli government has tightened the screw on the PNA
to crack down on terrorism. The militant Islamic Resistance
Movement (Hamas) has claimed responsibility for the bombing
attack.
</P>
<P>
Jabali has strongly denied his involvement in terrorism and
laughed off the Israeli order to arrest him. He warned Thursday
that if Israeli agents were sent to Gaza to arrest him, they
would never return to Israel.
</P>
<P>
Backing down from the threat to dispatch troops to capture
Jabali, Mordechai said that Israeli forces would arrest and try
Jabali only when he enters Israel.
</P>
<P>
Noting that the bombing attacks had derailed the peace process
when it was gathering momentum, Mordechai said any agreement
with the PNA should be based on promises that anti-Israeli
terrorism must be stopped.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, PNA officials blasted Israel's overreaction to the
Mahane Yehuda terror attack by reimposing a total closure on the
West Bank and Gaza Strip, canceling the planned resumption of
peace talks and threatening to dispatch troops to reenter
Palestinian self-rule areas to arrest terrorists.
</P>
<P>
PNA Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo told a news
conference held in Ramallah Friday that Israel's response to the
suicide bombings was irresponsible and attempted to weaken the
PNA led by Yasser Arafat.
</P>
<P>
Rabbo insisted that the PNA has been doing its best to combat
terrorism and the punitive measure taken by Israel would only
backfire. He warned that there would never be peace under such
conditions of collective punishment by Israel.
</P>
<P>
Hanan Ashrawi, PNA Minister of Higher Education, added that
Israel's tough measures would only place the situation under
further crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
