<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 06:42 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 16 Palestinian Cabinet Members Offer Resignation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Sixteen of the 18-member
Palestinian cabinet have submitted their resignation to President
Yasser Arafat over alleged corruption and mismanagement of funds,
JMCC, a Palestinian press service based in East Jerusalem,
reported today.
</P>
<P>
Agriculture Minister Abdul Jawad Saleh announced at a weekly
cabinet meeting in Ramallah Friday night that he and all but two
colleagues are ready to quit.
</P>
<P>
It is not yet clear whether Arafat accepts the resignation of
so many ministers. He is scheduled to fly to Cairo today for
talks with Egyptian President Hosni Mubarak over the situation
following the two suicide bombings in Jerusalem Wednesday,
killing 15 people and wounding over 170 others.
</P>
<P>
The Presidential office confirmed that Arafat had been asked
to consider the resignation at a suitable time, but declined to
give details.
</P>
<P>
The development came a day after the 88-member Palestinian
Council (PC) gave Arafat one month to dissolve the cabinet. The PC
also asked the president to form a new cabinet that includes
qualified persons and technocrats. The PC decision was adopted by
a vote 56-1.
</P>
<P>
"If no change is made by the end of September, we will make
inquiries, and if the situation remains the same, we will then
take the necessary measures," said PC President Ahmed Queria.
</P>
<P>
The PC made the decision following a report compiled by a panel
of 9 PC members detailing instances of the alleged corruption
committed by certain ministers.
</P>
<P>
It also recommended putting on trial two ministers: Minister
of Planning and International Cooperation Nabil Sha'ath and
Culture and Information Minister Yasser Abed Rabbo, who were the
only ones not offering to resign. The two ministers strongly
denied the allegation against them.
</P>
<P>
The PC decision is not legally binding, but does bear
pressure on Arafat. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
