<HEADLINE> China to Expect Tough Test at Challenge Tournament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Olympic runners-up China are
expecting a hard test at the China International Women's Softball
Challenge Tournament to be held here from August 5 to 10.
</P>
<P>
Organizers unveiled at a news conference here today that China
will not call back veteran players from abroad for the event,
which as well features Olympic third-place Australia, six-place
Chinese Taipei and Chinese Youth team.
</P>
<P>
The newly-reshuffled Chinese team, with only five players from
the silver-winning team at the 1996 Atlanta Olympic Games, are
expecting tough challenge from Australia, who come along with 11
Olympic bronze medalists, according to the Chinese Softball
Association.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese women's softball, on the ebb tide right now, are
trying to have their young players gaining experience at the
competition in preparation for next summer's World Softball
Championships, organizers said.
</P>
<P>
During last month's tour to United States, twice world
runners-up China lost all of their nine encounters with the
American hosts at the tournament which eventually won by
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The tournament, which had its first edition last year with
Australia triumphant through, will adopt triple round robin
format. 
</P>
</TEXT>
