<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0142 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Malaysia's CPO, Tin &AMP; Rubber Markets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia's markets of crude
palm oil (CPO) physicals, tin and rubber closed the week mixed
with CPO physicals lower and the other two higher.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the CPO physicals market received a boost
Thursday when two cargo surveyors, Caleb Brett and SGS (M) Private
Limited, put July palm oil exports at 722,389 tons and 710,836
tons respectively.
</P>
<P>
These two figures were higher compared with their previous
estimates for June at 634,753 tons and 611,368 tons respectively.
</P>
<P>
August South ended the week at 1,202.50 ringgit (about 462.5
U.S. dollars) per ton compared with 1,207.50 ringgit (about 464.42
U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the CPO physicals' rising trend at the end of this
week is unlikely to be sustained next week due to technical
reasons.
</P>
<P>
Technically, the market should be corrected next week when
players would have the opportunities for profit taking from recent
gains.
</P>
<P>
On the Kuala Lumpur Tin Market (KLTM), trading was quite
cautious this week, with the instability of the local currency
ringgit keeping players on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
During the week, the KLTM, which surged last week, ended
sharply higher as price rose 30 sen to 14.15 ringgit (about 5.442
U.S. dollars) per kg with accumulated turnover amounting to 751
tons compared with 515 tons last week.
</P>
<P>
Dealers said the upside potential of the KLTM was positive as
it should be further supported by a favorable outlook expected
from the LME next week.
</P>
<P>
The LME impact on the KLTM will be tremendous next week and the
KLTM is set to record further gains next week, they said.
</P>
<P>
On the Malaysian rubber market, the rubber prices ended the
week higher.
</P>
<P>
August RSS One settled the week five sen higher to 250.50 sen
(about 96.346 U.S. cents) per kg and SMR 20 firmed 5.50 sen to
250.00 sen (about 96.154 U.S. cents) per kg.
</P>
<P>
The International Natural Rubber Organization (INRO) daily
market indicator price for July 31 was at 192.87
Malaysian/Singapore cents (sen) from 189.60 cents (sen)
previously.
</P>
<P>
The five day moving average was at 192.06 cents (sen) against
187.89 cents (sen).
</P>
<P>
The Malaysian rubber prices are expected to extend its firm
trend next week in range-bound trading with the market awaiting
fresh factors to help determine short-term market direction.
</P>
<P>
Foreign inquiries are expected to be extended further,
especially from the Far East and Middle East.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
