<HEADLINE> Roundup: Manila Wages All-Out Anti-Drug War </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- An anti-drug campaign kicked off
by the mayor of Manila a month ago has quickly spread to other
parts of the Philippines, sparking off a nationwide war against
illegal drugs and drug lords and pushers.
</P>
<P>
On July 1, Manila Mayor Afredo Lim launched an all-out war
against drug pushers by mobilizing the police force in Manila to
raid the lair of wanted drug lord Florencio Parena. Parena eluded
arrest, but policemen uncovered 1.5 kilograms of methamphetamine
hydrochloride (shabu) and some high-power weapons.
</P>
<P>
The white-haired mayor also adopted a new measure to cope with
the drug traffickers. He ordered the police to spray in red paint
"This Is Drug Pusher's House, Please Keep Away" outside the houses
of suspected drug pushers and "Drug Pushers, Don't Destroy the
Young People's Future" at school gates.
</P>
<P>
Lim's campaign was welcomed by all students and ordinary
citizens. So far, the police have sprayed at least 235 houses in
Metro Manila. Lim said he would continue to do so to 100 other
public and private schools in the capital.
</P>
<P>
President Fidel Ramos threw his full support behind Lim,
describing the drug problem as the biggest threat to the country's
interests. Urging all local mayors to follow Lim's example, he
sought the overhaul of the 1972 Dangerous Drugs Act to ensure drug
lords and drug pushers their conviction.
</P>
<P>
"We will employ the full force of government against the
criminals and outlaws, especially their masterminds, the drug
lords and the financiers who persist in challenging the rule of
law and undermining the moral fabric of our society. We will hit
them hard, again and again," Ramos said.
</P>
<P>
Following the president's order, the police and military
quickly stepped up the crackdown on drug lords and drug
traffickers. In the past month, they killed six members of a drug
syndicate, rounded up 264 drug pushers, arrested seven scalawags
in the police and cremated 253 kilograms of shabu seized in the
country's largest drug sale.
</P>
<P>
Pressured by the powerful offensive, Parena gave himself up to
the police. After an initial interrogation, he confessed that he
sold 10-million-peso (350,000 U.S. dollars) worth of shabu every
week before his arrest.
</P>
<P>
The military is now going after 10 big-time drug syndicates in
the country, one of them reportedly much bigger than the 14-K gang
led by Alfredo Tiongco.
</P>
<P>
To capture Tiongco, the No.1 drug lord in the Philippines,
President Ramos has directed Justice Secretary Teofisto Guingona
and National Bureau of Investigation Director Santiago Toledo to
seek the help of the international police in tracking down him.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Congress also took concerted action. At present,
the lawmakers are considering approving nine anti-drug measures to
enable law enforcers to have more powers.
</P>
<P>
The bills would allow the seizure of drug lords' assets,
electronic surveillance of drug gangs and probe of bank records of
people charged with serious drug offenses.
</P>
<P>
The Congressmen are also mulling over the passage of
anti-racketing and anti-money laundering bills and proposing to
lower the amount of drug for death sentence conviction.
</P>
<P>
The Philippines has been a key transshipment point for
international drug syndicate due to its easily penetrable airports
and seaports and a long irregular coastline providing ideal entry
and exit points for drug smuggling.
</P>
<P>
The country becomes more vulnerable to drug traffickers given
its geographic closeness to major sources of illicit drugs, in
particular the "golden triangle" -- an area bordering Myanmar,
Thailand and Laos -- in Southeast Asia.
There are reportedly 560,000 drug pushers in Manila alone, where
the deal of shabu, the most popular drug, is reaching 9.5 billion
U.S. dollar a year.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the Philippines itself is turning into a big
consumption market of illegal drugs. According to the latest
report by the Narcotic Group of the Philippine National Police,
the number of drug users has risen by 250 percent to 1.7 million
over the past 10 years.
</P>
<P>
Most of these drug users were aged 15 to 29 and took an average
of 15 grams of drugs per head a month. 
</P>
</TEXT>
