<HEADLINE> Thai Islamic Spiritual Leader Dies at 70 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's Islamic spiritual
leader Prasert Muhammad died of heart failure in a local hospital
Friday at the age of 70, the local press reported today.
</P>
<P>
Prasert had served as an adviser to King Bhumibol Adulyadej on
Islamic affairs since 1981.
</P>
<P>
Thai Crown Prince Maha Vajiralongkorn presided over burial
rites at Marus Misideen Mosque in Bangkok Friday evening, which
was also attended by Thai Prime Minister Chavalit Yongchaiyudh and
Interior Minister Snoh Thienthong.
</P>
<P>
The Interior Ministry is expected to call a meeting of 29
provincial Islamic leaders to select a new Islamic leader to be
approved by King Bhumibol Adulyadej.
</P>
<P>
Muslims are Thailand's largest religious minority. Out of the
more than 60 million population now in the country, 95 percent are
Buddhists while about 4 percent are Muslims.
</P>
<P>
Islam might be introduced to the Malay Peninsula by Arab
traders and adventurers during the 13th century. Most Thai Muslims
are of Malay decent.
</P>
<P>
Muslims in Thailand are mainly concentrated in the southernmost
provinces of Narathiwat, Pattani, Yala and Satun. The Muslim
leader in Thailand is also known as Chularajamontri, or state
counselor for Islamic affairs.  
</P>
</TEXT>
