<HEADLINE> Weekly Report on Kuala Lumpur Stock Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The Composite Index (CI) on
the Kuala Lumpur Stock Exchange (KLSE) was under pressure this
week on concerns of the volatility of the ringgit (local currency)
on the foreign exchange market as well as the rising of interest
rates after the currency attack recently.
</P>
<P>
The CI shed 38.63 points to close the week at 1,002.63. The
Emas Index fell 8.45 points to 287.78, the second board index
eased 4.43 points to 545.86 and the Industrial Index dipped 39.26
points to 2,014.41 during the week.
</P>
<P>
Throughout the week, there were four new counters, Multi-Code
Electronics, Lankhorst, Latitude Tree and CCM Bioscience, listed
on the KLSE.
</P>
<P>
Multi-Code Electronics settled at 9.90 ringgit (3.8 U.S.
dollars) at the week's close, over its initial offer price of 3.80
ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Lankhorst recorded a premium of 7.00 ringgit over its initial
offer price of 4.50 ringgit to settle at 12.70 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
Latitude Tree settled at 7.80 ringgit over its offer price of
2.70 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
And CCM Bioscience which was listed on the last day of the
trading week ended its first day at 6.65 ringgit over its initial
offer price of 2.80 ringgit.
</P>
<P>
This week, the top 10 active stocks were Econstates, Taiping,
Renong, MBF Capital, Anson, Chase Perdana, Pelangi, Eupe
Corporation, Tongkah and Ho Wah Genting, with the first six
falling marginally and the rest gaining also marginally.
</P>
<P>
The weekly main board ready turnover shrunk to 920.498 million
shares worth 5.053 billion ringgit (about 1.943 billion U.S.
dollars) from 1.107 billion shares valued at 6.236 billion ringgit
(about 2.398 billion U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
The second board turnover eased to 222.880 million shares worth
2.770 billion ringgit (about 1.065 billion U.S. dollars) from
270.760 million shares valued at 3.091 billion ringgit (about
1.189 billion U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Direct business transactions amounted to 306.960 million shares
worth 2.033 billion ringgit (about 781.923 million U.S. dollars)
from 227.088 million shares valued at 1.993 billion ringgit (about
766.538 million U.S. dollars) last week.
</P>
<P>
On sectoral basis, consumer products accounted for 34.211
million shares traded, industrial products 125.444 million shares,
construction 79.715 million shares, trading/services 125.952
million shares, infrastructure 7.938 million shares, finance
113.224 million shares, hotels 2.792 million shares, properties
314.845 million shares, plantation 22.722 million shares, mining
10.724 million shares, trusts 452,000 shares, closed fund 748,800
shares, loans 25.370 million shares and call warrants 54.438
million shares.
</P>
<P>
The KLSE is expected to remain jittery and move sideways next
week with the CI anticipated to move in a range of between 1,000
and 1,050 points, an analyst said, adding however support will be
seen on the second board after its recent downtrend.  
</P>
</TEXT>
