<HEADLINE> Spain Takes Actions to Save Mediterranean Fish </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MADRID, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Spanish government announced
today that it will set up a fish reserve and enlarge territorial
waters in the Mediterranean to help save the endangered fish
species there.
</P>
<P>
The new fish reserve will stretch from the Cape of Gata in
southern Spain eastward to the start of French territorial waters.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Spanish territorial waters will be extended from the
present 12 nautical miles to 49 miles.
</P>
<P>
Scientists have warned repeatedly that the number of red tuna in
the Mediterranean sea, the sole breeding site on Earth for this
rare fish on verge of extinction, is diminishing.
</P>
<P>
They urged all countries concerned to take effective measures
to protect the species.
</P>
<P>
The Spanish government said fishing boats would be fined if
they targeted red tuna in the designated waters. 
</P>
</TEXT>
