<HEADLINE> Thailand's Price Index up in July </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Thailand's consumer price index
(CPI) was 140.0 in July, up 4.9 percent on a year-on-year basis,
the Thai commerce ministry said on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The figure was also 6 percent higher than that in June.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the CPI hike in July to higher prices
of food, beverage and oil as a result of the baht's de facto
depreciation following the Thai central bank's decision to float
the Thai currency on July 2.
</P>
<P>
The food and beverage sector index rose by 6.9 percent as
compared with the same month last year, while the non-food sector
index climbed up 3.5 percent, according to the statistics released
by the ministry's Business Economics Department.
</P>
<P>
Prices of rice and crop products, fresh chicken, eggs and fuels
recorded the highest increase last month.
</P>
<P>
The price of rice jumped up 4.7 percent from June and was up
30.1 percent year-on-year, while chicken prices rose 0.3 percent
from June and was 5.9 percent higher year-on-year.
</P>
<P>
Thai commerce minister Narongchai Akrasanee Friday said that
the July CPI figures were reasonable under the current
circumstances and the inflationary pressure was under control.
</P>
<P>
Some commerce ministry officials said that food and fuel prices
are expected to continue to rise in august, even before suppliers
use up their inventories, and the august CPI is likely to rise
sharply.  
</P>
</TEXT>
