<HEADLINE> 30-year Sino-US Deal Starts </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The first batch of 35,000 tons of
aluminium oxide has arrived in Qingdao from the United States,
which marked the official beginning of a 30-year contract between
China and the United States, according to today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
The contract was signed by the China National Non-ferrous
Metals Industry Trading Group, a subsidiary of the China National
Non-Ferrous Metals Industry Corp. (CNNC), and the Aluminium
Company of America (ALCOA) in London last September.
</P>
<P>
According to the contract, China will import between 400,000
and one million tons of aluminium oxide from the US company at
cost price each year for a period of 30 years.
</P>
<P>
The CNNC invested 80 million US dollars in the project. And a
dozen foreign banks led by Credit Lyonnais of France also provided
160 million US dollars worth of preferential loans to the
project. The term of the loans is ten years.
</P>
<P>
Officials from the CNNC said quality was the decisive factor in
the choice of ALCOA. The contract will help ease the shortages of
the material in the domestic market.
</P>
<P>
Imports of aluminium products in the first half reached 112,600
tons, an increase of 23.7 percent year-on-year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
