<HEADLINE> Chile Calls for Greater Latin American Role </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MONTEVIDEO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Chilean President Eduardo Frei
today called on Latin American countries to play a greater role in
regional integration and quickly revive regional economy.
</P>
<P>
At a meeting of the Latin American Integration Association
(LAIA) in Montevideo, Frei said Latin American states should make
greater efforts to have their voice heard in the world to help
change the current situation of "marching in the rear of the
developed countries."
</P>
<P>
The association was set up in 1960 to promote regional trade
ties.
</P>
<P>
Frei, starting a visit to Uruguay Wednesday, urged the LAIA
members to take the initiative in the negotiations under way for
the creation of the Free Trade Area of Americas (FTAA) by 2005,
and within the World Trade Organization (WTO).
</P>
<P>
The 11 LAIA countries, including Brazil, Argentina, Mexico and
Peru, must define their interests and set common guidelines in the
negotiations with hemispherical and world trade bodies, he said.
</P>
<P>
Acknowledging the "dynamic, positive and integrating" role
played by LAIA, Frei called on the group to explore new avenues to
"create real interdependence among our countries." 
</P>
