<HEADLINE> ASEAN Maps Out Peace Plan On Cambodia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, August 2 (Xinhua) -- ASEAN foreign ministers preparing
to embark on a peace mission to Cambodia will present a "general
idea" for peace when they meet Cambodian Second Prime Minister Hun
Sen today.
</P>
<P>
Indonesian Foreign Minister Ali Alatas said here Friday night
that  the proposal, formulated on behalf of the Association of
Southeast Asian Nations (ASEAN), has already been accepted by
First Prime Minister Norodom Ranariddh, as well as Cambodia's King
Norodom Sihanouk.
</P>
<P>
Alatas along with Philippine Foreign Secretary Domingo Siazon
and Thai Foreign Minister Prachuab Chaiyasarn have been assigned
to meet Hun Sen to seek a peaceful settlement of the Cambodian
problem.
</P>
<P>
A Foreign Ministry official said Alatas was leaving here this
morning for Phnom Penh as a first step in ASEAN's renewed efforts
to help resolve the political crisis in Cambodia.
</P>
<P>
"What is important is that now Prime Minister Hun Sen agrees to
hear ASEAN's views, which previously were seen by him as an
intervention in Cambodia's internal affairs," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
"We will see how Hun Sen reacts, if we reach a point that
promises settlement, we will talk again with Prince Ranariddh and
perhaps also the King. The process will continue," Alatas said.
</P>
<P>
ASEAN admitted Myanmar and Laos as new members but deferred
Cambodia's entry into its ranks when its foreign ministers met in
Kuala Lumpur last month. ASEAN now groups Brunei, Indonesia,
Malaysia, the Philippines, Singapore, Thailand, Vietnam, Laos and
Myanmar.  
