<HEADLINE> Shanghai Firm Given Fine for Using Data Illegally </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai Bartech Data Information
Corp. was ordered to pay 926,500 yuan in compensation to a Beijing
company after the former was found guilty of the charges of
infringing on the latter's commercial secrets.
</P>
<P>
The ruling was made by Beijing No. 1 Intermediate People's
Court after a year of judicial proceedings including
investigations and consultations by experts, today's "China Daily"
reported.
</P>
<P>
The court also ordered the Shanghai firm to stop illegal use of
information commodities made by Beijing Sunlight Data Co. of the
State Information Center.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper said this is the first case involving information
infringement through unfair competitions.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Sunlight Data sued the Shanghai firm for five
million yuan in damages the latter had caused by illegally
broadcasting a comprehensive stock listing collected by Sunlight
Data from China's 15 major stock trading offices to its own users
as a way of attracting users from the stock market.
</P>
<P>
The infringement was discovered by the Beijing company after
receiving complaints and protests from several stock trading
offices.
</P>
<P>
The number of cases inviolation of intellectual property rights
handled by Chinese courts last year was 11.8 percent higher than
that in 1995. The figure for the first five months of this year
was 15.3 percent higher than the same period of 1996, according to
the newspaper.  
</P>
</TEXT>
