<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Develops World's Largest Metal Cutting Machine </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, July 28 (Xinhua) -- Technicians in China's Xinjiang
Uygur Autonomous Region, northwest China, have developed a
new rolling machine tool, an electric rolling machine that
is the largest and newest of its kind in the world.
</P>
<P>
The machine is light, simple, and compact in size -- useful
features for a new generation of machine tools.
</P>
<P>
The new machine can handle 500 to 1,000 grams of super hard,
super adhesive, super crisp and special electric conductive
materials per minute while the traditional model can only
process several grams per minute, said Ye Liangcai, the developer.
</P>
<P>
It consumes only two or three kwh of electricity to cut 1,000 grams
of metal, 20-25 times less than traditional machines, and its
service life is five to ten times longer than traditional machines.
</P>
<P>
The machine uses an electrofusion pop-in technique invented by
Ye Liangcai, head of a research institute for electrofusion pop-in
technology in the northwestern region.
</P>
<P>
The machine will be soon shipped to Canada which has ordered
it.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0177 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Peru Marks 50th Anniversary of 200-Mile Sea Limit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LIMA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Peru commemorated today the 50th
anniversary of the declaration of its 200-mile territorial sea
limit.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Ferrero Costa said at a party that the
200-mile thesis has been extended to other countries and
continents and recognized as a rule of international law.
</P>
<P>
"We cannot forget the joint action adopted by Chile, Ecuador,
and Peru after 1952, with the Declaration of the 200-Mile Maritime
Zone, or Declaration of Santiago," he said.
</P>
<P>
On August 18, 1952, Chile, Ecuador and Peru signed the
Declaration of Santiago on the maritime zone, a document that
became the first international instrument of multilateral
character that consecrated the 200-mile thesis.
</P>
<P>
With this declaration, the Southern Pacific states presented to
the international community their right, as coastal countries, to
protect, conserve, and use their natural resources in the marked
zones.
</P>
<P>
The declaration opened the door for the creation of the
Southern Pacific Permanent Commission, which marked the start of a
revolution aimed at getting international recognition of the
maritime rights of the Southeastern Pacific.
</P>
<P>
After the signing of the Declaration of Santiago, other Latin
American countries decided to adopt the 200-mile thesis. They
included Nicaragua, Argentina, Panama, Uruguay, Brazil, Costa Rica
and Colombia.
</P>
<P>
The consecration of the 200-mile thesis was achieved during the
Third Conference of the United Nations on Sea Law in 1982. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0178 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
