<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Ethnic Dropouts Return to School </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
URUMQI, August 2 (Xinhua) -- The "Spring Bud" Project has
helped over 2,000 young female dropouts in the Xinjiang Uygur
Autonomous Region, NW China, return to school.
</P>
<P>
The goal of the program, "Spring Bud", jointly sponsored by the
All-China Women's Federation and China Children's Foundation, is
to help a large number of China's dropouts return to school.
Xinjiang, one of the program's ten major targets, is home to
110,000 female dropouts, some 90 percent of whom belong to ethnic
minorities.
</P>
<P>
Participation in the program enabled local education
departments to establish a special six-year course of study for
young females living in compact minority nationality communities
in remote poverty-stricken areas. The program enabled Xinjiang to
offer either tuition reductions or exemptions and to hire
additional female teachers.
</P>
<P>
The program places special emphasis on providing professional
training which enables female students acquire some practical
skills in areas such as aquatics breeding, agronomy, embroidery
and processing, as well as in culture and science.
</P>
<P>
Governments at all levels, all social sectors and military
units in Xinjiang have provided various forms of assistance,
including school buildings, living quarters and supplies.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
