<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Increasing Overseas Investment in South China's Agriculture </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Huizhou City in south China's
Guangdong Province has become a popular place for overseas
investment, thanks to local natural resources and favorable
geographical conditions.
</P>
<P>
The city had 227 overseas-funded agricultural projects by the
end of last year, using more than 484 million US dollars worth of
overseas funds.
</P>
<P>
The majority of overseas investment was used for afforestation,
orchards, and for building farms, cold storage plants, and
processing plants. In recent years more than 55 million US dollars
of overseas investment were used on 3,700 ha. for agricultural
development, and the city has added 15,000 ha. of orchards, 10,000
ha. of forests, and 600 ha. of freshwater farms.
</P>
<P>
The city hopes to use overseas funding for local wastelands,
barren mountains, water resources, and low-yield farmland and
paddies.
</P>
<P>
In addition to funds from Hong Kong and Macao, the city also
attracts a large amount of overseas investment from China's Taiwan
province, Japan, Denmark, Malaysia and Saudi Arabia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
