<HEADLINE> Brazilian Gross Domestic Product To Grow 4% </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
RIO DE JANEIRO, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Brazilian gross
domestic product (GDP) in 1997 will increase 4 percent as
compared to that of 1996, announced the Applied Economic Research
Institute (IPEA).
</P>
<P>
Agriculture and livestock, with an estimated expansion of 6.4
percent, will be the main contributor to the 4 percent growth of
the GDP, according to a recent IPEA report.
</P>
<P>
Industry will close the year with a 3.9 percent growth, and the
services sector must expand its production by 3.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
The balance of trade deficit this year will be 11 billion U.S.
dollars as against the 5.5 billion dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Last year's GDP grew 3.9 percent, according to official
figures. 
