<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Automatic Bed Helps Elderly And Handicapped </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua)-- An automatic nursing bed has been
developed in China for the handicapped, the elderly, and patients
who suffer from chronic illnesses.
</P>
<P>
The fully computerized bed was developed by the Beijing
Hangxing Machine Manufacturing Corp. and a Japanese research
center, and will mean greater convenience for people who are
confined to bed.
</P>
<P>
With this particular bed, a patient can sit up or lie down,
move to a wheelchair, take a bath, use the toilet, or even change
the bed sheet, all with just the push of a button. He or she will be
warned of possible machine failures, and if there are power
outages, it can be manually operated. Certain models even respond
to a spoken command
</P>
<P>
The number of elderly in China has been on a steady increase,
and the number of handicapped people had reached 60 million by the
end of 1996, and 8.8 million of those are disabled.
</P>
<P>
The country has set up more than 40,000 nursing homes, taking
care of nearly 600,000 elderly. The government also had provided
the handicapped with more than 700,000 different pieces of
equipment to help them, between 1990 and 1995.
</P>
<P>
The automatic nursing bed is expected to go into mass
production by the end of the year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
