<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Ethnic Minorities Benefit From International Aid </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Kunming, August 2 (Xinhua) -- Some 600,000 farmers, mainly
ethnic minorities, in China's Yunnan Province have begun to have
better lives thanks to an international aid-the-poor program.
</P>
<P>
In 1992, the province began to get international assistance in
developing agriculture, and has used more than 300 million yuan in
loans for the effort from the World Food Program (WFP), the
International Fund for Agricultural Development (IFAD), and the
Japanese government.
</P>
<P>
The Agricultural Development Program of Yunnan Ethnic
Minorities in Simao Mountainous Areas started in 1992, with 280
million yuan in low-interest loans from IFAD for 35 townships of
540,000 farmers.
</P>
<P>
The program has helped 20 percent of the people there escape
poverty, and 378,000 people have 235 kg more grain per capita, and
a per capita income more than one and a half times larger
</P>
<P>
The WFP spent 28.64 million yuan in three counties to help
120,000 poor people, and the project area produces 83,000 tons of
grain annually now, compared with 54,000 tons in 1992.
</P>
<P>
The Japanese government donated 270 million Japanese yen to two
poverty-stricken counties to help add 52,000 tons of grain, and
helped more than double farmers' income. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
