<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0189 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Personal Incomes and Spending Up in June </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. personal incomes
increased by 0.6 percent in June, the biggest gain in three
months, U.S. Commerce Department reported today.
</P>
<P>
The department also said that the personal spending was up
by 0.3 percent in June following a 0.1 percent rise in May.
</P>
<P>
Personal incomes rose to an annual rate of 6.87 trillion
dollars in June, up from 6.82 trillion a month earlier. The 0.6
percent increase was the biggest since an identical advance in
March.
</P>
<P>
Private wages and salaries, the most closely watched component
of Americans' income, rose by 31.8 billion dollars, compared to a
gain of 12 billion in May.
</P>
<P>
Disposable income -- income after taxes -- increased by 0.5
percent after advancing just 0.1 percent in April and 0.3 percent
in May.
</P>
<P>
The report said spending totaled an annual rate of 5.44
trillion dollars, compared to 5.43 trillion in May.
</P>
<P>
Spending on durable goods -- items expected to last more than
three years -- slipped by 3.7 billion dollars and wiped out a 3.5
billion gain the previous month. Spending on nondurable goods rose
by 4.4 billion dollars and spending on services was up 14 billion.
</P>
<P>
Consumer spending represents two-thirds of the U.S. economic
activity.
</P>
<P>
The combination of incomes and spending meant that Americans'
savings rate -- savings as a percentage of disposable income --
was 4.4 percent in June, up from 4.1 percent a month earlier.
</P>
<P>
The income and spending percentages were not adjusted for
inflation. When adjusted, disposable incomes were up 0.4 percent,
compared to a 0.3 percent increase in May. Spending rose 0.1
percent, less than the 0.3 percent gain the previous month.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0190 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Redundant Workers Enter Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, August 2 (Xinhua) -- China's State Statistical Bureau
(SSB) reported that private businesses and household enterprises
have emerged as the major reemployment channel for redundant
workers.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper "China Information" quoted bureau statistics
showing that the private sector in urban areas employed nearly 25
million people by the end of June this year, up 1.7 million on
1996 figures. Redundant workers not only accounted for the
majority of workers mentioned above, but also for an increasing
proportion of the private sector workforce in rural areas.
</P>
<P>
The number of staff and workers in state-owned enterprises fell
by approximately one million, with the figure for collective
enterprises in urban areas decreasing by 773,000.
</P>
<P>
Nonetheless, the booming private sector has led to steady
increases in total employment.
</P>
<P>
Redundant workers and facing increasingly fierce competition in
finding new job opportunities. Local governments and former
employers have responded by offering retraining programs.
</P>
</TEXT>
