<HEADLINE> French Sebastien Deleigne Wins Men's Title </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SOFIA, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Sebastien Deleigne sealed the
victory with 5,575 points in the men's individual event at the
Modern Pentathlon World Championships here on Friday.
</P>
<P>
The 30-year-old, a physical teacher, won his country the first
gold medal at the Modern Pentathlon World Championships for ten
years.
</P>
<P>
"This is a significant achievement for me and my country. I
have prepared very well for the championships and that is crucial
for the victory," said Deleigne, European Champion and bronze
medalist at the 1993 world championships.
</P>
<P>
Deleigne took the lead as early as in the first event,
shooting, and kept his lead all the way to the end.
</P>
<P>
Dmitry Svatkovski from Russia finished runner-up while Andrejus
Zadneprovskis from Lithuania was third.
</P>
<P>
The 1996 Atalanta Olympic champion Alexandar Parigin of
Kazakhstan finished only seventh. 
