<HEADLINE> Latin American Economic News Briefs (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MEXICO CITY, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The following are the major
economic news briefs from Latin American countries over the past
few days:
</P>
<P>
MANAGUA -- A mission of the seven biggest firms in the
agroindustrial sector of Colombia visited Nicaragua this week to
explore the possibility of investments and marketing of their
products.
</P>
<P>
"The reactivation of the Nicaraguan economy prompts us to enter
this market," said Colombia ProExport programs coordinator
Sergio Quijano.
</P>
<P>
The Colombian businessmen will return seven months from now to
have a better contact with Nicaraguan businessmen.
</P>
<P>
CARACAS -- The state oil enterprise Petroleos de Venezuela
(PDVSA) will pay the treasury 11.5 billion U.S. dollars in 1997 in
taxes and royalties, which represents a 35 percent increase over
the previous yeasr.
</P>
<P>
The figure reprsents 14 percent of the country's gross domestic
product for this year.
</P>
<P>
PANAMA CITY -- The Interamerican Development Bank (IADB)
approved a 45-million-dollar loan for Panama to improve the
quality and efficiency of the drinking water and sewage in the
capital.
</P>
<P>
The resources will finance the restructuration of the Aqueducts
and Sewage Systems Institute (IDDAN) to promote an opening of that
sector.
</P>
<P>
BUENOS AIRES -- Canadian mining investments in Argentina that
started in 1990 and will continue until the year 2000 have
accumulated 1.2 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The Canadian capitals have also been channeled to the oil,
agriculture, forestry, and telecommunications and transports
sectors.
</P>
<P>
Argentina is for Canada an emerging and potential market
because of the projected growth of 5 percent of its gross domestic
product and for its integration with its neighbors in the Common
Market, said the Canadian embassy.
</P>
<P>
MEXICO CITY -- Mexican footwear manufacturers will export this
year 30 million pairs of shoes, which shows a 100 percent growth
of the sector in the last two years.
</P>
<P>
Export is the only choice for the growth of the sector, said
the president of the National Chamber of the Footwear Industry,
Jorge Elias Calles.
</P>
<P>
BRASILIA -- Brazilian exports reached in July the unprecedented
amount of 4.843 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
The product that contributed the most to exports growth was soy
beans, besides other merchandise that registered excellent sales
abroad, such as grains and motor vehicles
</P>
</TEXT>
