<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kipketer, the Most Talented Runner Kenya Lost </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- With Wilson Kipketer standing on
the track, even the most ardent Kenyan fans admit, their world
class runners have no chance to beat this 26-year-old Kenyan-born
Dane at the current 6th World Athletics Championships.
</P>
<P>
To most Kenyans, Haile Gebrselassie of Ethiopia is versatile,
Morrocco's Hachim El Guerrouj and Salah Hissou may threaten their
middle and long distance glories, but their "own" Kipketer is a
sure bet to snatch the men's 800-meter title from his former
Kenyan brothers.
</P>
<P>
After equalling Sebastian Coe's 16-year-old world 800m record
of one minute 41.73 seconds early this month, Kipketer has been
tipped as the brightest shining star at the championships.
</P>
<P>
In a country where blood runs deep in the veins, Kipketer might
be a Dane, but Kenyans could not care less about him. "He is one
of us still. No medal is more valued and celebrted in Kenya than
the 800m gold. Our adults and youth alike think nicely of him, "
said Peter Njenga, a Kenyan journalist.
</P>
<P>
Kenya had a long history of winning the 800 meters in world
major competitions. Wilson Kipkurgut Chumo won Kenya's first
Olympic medal -- a bronze -- in the 1964 Tokyo Games. From the
Second World Championships in 1987, Kenya never let the event
world title slip from their hands. Billy Konchellah won the crown
twice in 1987 and 1991 before Wiliam Tanui and Paul Ruto's
triumphs in 1993 and 1995. But this time, Kipketer is the hardest
nut for gifted Kenyans to crack.
</P>
<P>
Moses Kiptanui, the 3,000-meter steeplechase world record
holder and triple world champion, may be the greatest
steeplechaser of his era, but is certainly viewed ordinary at home
if compares him with Kipketer.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer is a hero whose love for adventure has made him shift
base to Denmark. He joined the Denmark's nationality last
October. This, according to the majority of Kenyans, is
understandable.
</P>
<P>
They think it shows a man of determination and hard work.
According to Njenga, Kipketer has built a house in his rural
hometown in Kenya and brought his wife home. "So in the
championships, Kenyans will cheer him on and consider his gold
medal as good as theirs."
</P>
<P>
Commonwealth Games champion Patrick Konchellah is tipped only
for the silver. The Kenyan is the only other runner beside
Kipketer to run under 1:44 in the world this season.
</P>
<P>
Kipketer said here yesterday that his aim at the meet is to
shatter the 800 meters world record. "I am a Dane right now, but
I don't hate my native country. The glory will also go to Kenya,"
claimed the defending world champion, who was denied by Kenya last
year to compete in the Olympics for Denmark. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19970802.0204 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1997-08-02 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> IAAF 6th World Athletics Championships Open in Athens </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, August 1 (Xinhua) -- The Sixth World Athletics
Championships opened at the ancient marble Panathinaikon Stadium
Friday night with 200 countries and regions sending teams to
compete in the largest single sport event ever in history.
</P>
<P>
The event has registered the best attended sport competition in
history. The last year's Olympic Games had 197 participating
teams and the 1995 World Championships had 191 delegations. A new
record total of 1,957 athletes will take part in the 9-day contest
starting tomorrow at the newly-built Olympic Stadium.
</P>
<P>
After the International Amateur Athletics Federation's
President Primo Nebiolo's opening remark, Costantinos
Stephanopoulos, President of the Greek Republic, declared
officially open the meet.
</P>
<P>
After the parade of the athletes, the organisers offered the
world a spectacular audio-visual show to display the sacred spirit
of the athletics.
</P>
<P>
The world famous Greek artist Vangelis -- "The God Father of
electronic music" -- used the latest technology from around the
world to create a series of artistic elements at the Panathinaikon
Stadium, venue of the First Olympic Games of the modern era in
1896.
</P>
<P>
The competition will start on Saturday with two finals
arranged. In the men's 20-kilometer walk, Olympic champion
Jefferson Perez of Ecudor, Olympic bronze medallist Ilya Markov of
Russia and World Cup silver winner Daniel Garcia of Mexico are
medal hopefuls.
</P>
<P>
The men's shot put world title is set to be won by Olympic
champion and world record holder Randy Barnes of the United
States. The American is the year's best mark setter with a
22.03-meter throw. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
