<HEADLINE> U.S., Azerbaijani Presidents Hold Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, August 1 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
held talks on Friday with Azerbaijan's President Heydar Aliyer at
the White House and both leaders agreed that it was important to
expand the partnership between the two countries through
strengthening bilateral cooperation in the political, security,
economic and commercial spheres.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents' meeting followed a series of sessions this
week for Aliyer with U.S. senior officials, including Defense
Secretary William Cohen and Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin.
</P>
<P>
During the presidents' talks, a batch of deals were signed,
which was said to be able to clear the way for U.S. oil companies
like Chevron, Exxon, Mobil and Amoco, to participate in oil
exploration, development and production in Azerbaijan.
</P>
<P>
Both presidents said in a joint statement on U.S.-Azerbaijan
relations, issued after their meeting, that they would exert their
efforts to make U.S. companies extensively participate "in the
development and transport of Azerbaijan's oil and gas resources."
</P>
<P>
Last Week, U.S. Undersecretary of State Stuart Eizenstat
testified before a Senate committee that the United States is
managing to build a working relationship with Central Asian
nations because, if failed to do so, Iran waiting in the wings,
would step in whenever it gets any chances.
</P>
<P>
Clinton also supported to rescind sanctions against Azerbaijan,
imposed by the United states in 1992 because of the Azerbaijani
conflict with Armenia, which he said limited potential cooperation
between the United States and Azerbaijan. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
