<HEADLINE> New York Stocks Continue to Slip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW YORK, August 1 (Xinhua) -- Stocks on Wall Street ended
modestly lower today, rebounding after tumbling as inflation
worries resurfaced on news that raw materials prices jumped in
July.
</P>
<P>
The Dow Jones industrial average fell just 28.57 to 8,194.04,
up 80.60 for the week. The index tumbled nearly 120 points after
this morning's report by the National Association of Purchasing
Management (NAPM).
</P>
<P>
Broader-stock indicators also recovered over the final hour.
</P>
<P>
Declining issues outnumbered advancers by a 7-to-4 margin on
the New York Stock Exchange, where volume totaled 511.63 million
shares as against 547.87 million in the previous session.
</P>
<P>
The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock list fell 7.15 to 947.14, and
the NYSE composite index fell 3.51 to 490.99.
</P>
<P>
The Nasdaq composite index rose 0.51 to 1,594.32, and the
American Stock Exchange composite index fell 2.11 to 644.19.
</P>
<P>
The NAPM's survey of factory executives showed that
manufacturing activity accelerated to the highest level in almost
three years during July.
</P>
<P>
As bond prices fell, the yield on the 30-year Treasury surged
as high as 6.46 percent after touching a 17-month low of 6.29
percent on Thursday.  
</P>
</TEXT>
